01â 1:1 In the beginning when God created the heavens and the earth,
01â 1:2 the earth was a formless void and darkness covered the face of the deep, while a wind from God swept over the face of the waters.
01â 1:3 Then God said, "Let there be light"; and there was light.
01â 1:4 And God saw that the light was good; and God separated the light from the darkness.
01â 1:5 God called the light Day, and the darkness he called Night. And there was evening and there was morning, the first day.
01â 1:6 And God said, "Let there be a dome in the midst of the waters, and let it separate the waters from the waters."
01â 1:7 So God made the dome and separated the waters that were under the dome from the waters that were above the dome. And it was so.
01â 1:8 God called the dome Sky. And there was evening and there was morning, the second day.
01â 1:9 And God said, "Let the waters under the sky be gathered together into one place, and let the dry land appear." And it was so.
01â 1:10 God called the dry land Earth, and the waters that were gathered together he called Seas. And God saw that it was good.
01â 1:11 Then God said, "Let the earth put forth vegetation: plants yielding seed, and fruit trees of every kind on earth that bear fruit with the seed in it." And it was so.
01â 1:12 The earth brought forth vegetation: plants yielding seed of every kind, and trees of every kind bearing fruit with the seed in it. And God saw that it was good.
01â 1:13 And there was evening and there was morning, the third day.
01â 1:14 And God said, "Let there be lights in the dome of the sky to separate the day from the night; and let them be for signs and for seasons and for days and years,
01â 1:15 and let them be lights in the dome of the sky to give light upon the earth." And it was so.
01â 1:16 God made the two great lights--the greater light to rule the day and the lesser light to rule the night--and the stars.
01â 1:17 God set them in the dome of the sky to give light upon the earth,
01â 1:18 to rule over the day and over the night, and to separate the light from the darkness. And God saw that it was good.
01â 1:19 And there was evening and there was morning, the fourth day.
01â 1:20 And God said, "Let the waters bring forth swarms of living creatures, and let birds fly above the earth across the dome of the sky."
01â 1:21 So God created the great sea monsters and every living creature that moves, of every kind, with which the waters swarm, and every winged bird of every kind. And God saw that it was good.
01â 1:22 God blessed them, saying, "Be fruitful and multiply and fill the waters in the seas, and let birds multiply on the earth."
01â 1:23 And there was evening and there was morning, the fifth day.
01â 1:24 And God said, "Let the earth bring forth living creatures of every kind: cattle and creeping things and wild animals of the earth of every kind." And it was so.
01â 1:25 God made the wild animals of the earth of every kind, and the cattle of every kind, and everything that creeps upon the ground of every kind. And God saw that it was good.
01â 1:26 Then God said, "Let us make humankind in our image, according to our likeness; and let them have dominion over the fish of the sea, and over the birds of the air, and over the cattle, and over all the wild animals of the earth, and over every creeping thing that creeps upon the earth."
01â 1:27 So God created humankind in his image, in the image of God he created them; male and female he created them.
01â 1:28 God blessed them, and God said to them, "Be fruitful and multiply, and fill the earth and subdue it; and have dominion over the fish of the sea and over the birds of the air and over every living thing that moves upon the earth."
01â 1:29 God said, "See, I have given you every plant yielding seed that is upon the face of all the earth, and every tree with seed in its fruit; you shall have them for food.
01â 1:30 And to every beast of the earth, and to every bird of the air, and to everything that creeps on the earth, everything that has the breath of life, I have given every green plant for food." And it was so.
01â 1:31 God saw everything that he had made, and indeed, it was very good. And there was evening and there was morning, the sixth day.
01â 2:1 Thus the heavens and the earth were finished, and all their multitude.
01â 2:2 And on the seventh day God finished the work that he had done, and he rested on the seventh day from all the work that he had done.
01â 2:3 So God blessed the seventh day and hallowed it, because on it God rested from all the work that he had done in creation.
01â 2:4 These are the generations of the heavens and the earth when they were created. In the day that the LORD God made the earth and the heavens,
01â 2:5 when no plant of the field was yet in the earth and no herb of the field had yet sprung up--for the LORD God had not caused it to rain upon the earth, and there was no one to till the ground;
01â 2:6 but a stream would rise from the earth, and water the whole face of the ground--
01â 2:7 then the LORD God formed man from the dust of the ground, and breathed into his nostrils the breath of life; and the man became a living being.
01â 2:8 And the LORD God planted a garden in Eden, in the east; and there he put the man whom he had formed.
01â 2:9 Out of the ground the LORD God made to grow every tree that is pleasant to the sight and good for food, the tree of life also in the midst of the garden, and the tree of the knowledge of good and evil.
01â 2:10 A river flows out of Eden to water the garden, and from there it divides and becomes four branches.
01â 2:11 The name of the first is Pishon; it is the one that flows around the whole land of Havilah, where there is gold;
01â 2:12 and the gold of that land is good; bdellium and onyx stone are there.
01â 2:13 The name of the second river is Gihon; it is the one that flows around the whole land of Cush.
01â 2:14 The name of the third river is Tigris, which flows east of Assyria. And the fourth river is the Euphrates.
01â 2:15 The LORD God took the man and put him in the garden of Eden to till it and keep it.
01â 2:16 And the LORD God commanded the man, "You may freely eat of every tree of the garden;
01â 2:17 but of the tree of the knowledge of good and evil you shall not eat, for in the day that you eat of it you shall die."
01â 2:18 Then the LORD God said, "It is not good that the man should be alone; I will make him a helper as his partner."
01â 2:19 So out of the ground the LORD God formed every animal of the field and every bird of the air, and brought them to the man to see what he would call them; and whatever the man called every living creature, that was its name.
01â 2:20 The man gave names to all cattle, and to the birds of the air, and to every animal of the field; but for the man there was not found a helper as his partner.
01â 2:21 So the LORD God caused a deep sleep to fall upon the man, and he slept; then he took one of his ribs and closed up its place with flesh.
01â 2:22 And the rib that the LORD God had taken from the man he made into a woman and brought her to the man.
01â 2:23 Then the man said, "This at last is bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh; this one shall be called Woman, for out of Man this one was taken."
01â 2:24 Therefore a man leaves his father and his mother and clings to his wife, and they become one flesh.
01â 2:25 And the man and his wife were both naked, and were not ashamed.
01â 3:1 Now the serpent was more crafty than any other wild animal that the LORD God had made. He said to the woman, "Did God say, 'You shall not eat from any tree in the garden'?"
01â 3:2 The woman said to the serpent, "We may eat of the fruit of the trees in the garden;
01â 3:3 but God said, 'You shall not eat of the fruit of the tree that is in the middle of the garden, nor shall you touch it, or you shall die.'"
01â 3:4 But the serpent said to the woman, "You will not die;
01â 3:5 for God knows that when you eat of it your eyes will be opened, and you will be like God, knowing good and evil."
01â 3:6 So when the woman saw that the tree was good for food, and that it was a delight to the eyes, and that the tree was to be desired to make one wise, she took of its fruit and ate; and she also gave some to her husband, who was with her, and he ate.
01â 3:7 Then the eyes of both were opened, and they knew that they were naked; and they sewed fig leaves together and made loincloths for themselves.
01â 3:8 They heard the sound of the LORD God walking in the garden at the time of the evening breeze, and the man and his wife hid themselves from the presence of the LORD God among the trees of the garden.
01â 3:9 But the LORD God called to the man, and said to him, "Where are you?"
01â 3:10 He said, "I heard the sound of you in the garden, and I was afraid, because I was naked; and I hid myself."
01â 3:11 He said, "Who told you that you were naked? Have you eaten from the tree of which I commanded you not to eat?"
01â 3:12 The man said, "The woman whom you gave to be with me, she gave me fruit from the tree, and I ate."
01â 3:13 Then the LORD God said to the woman, "What is this that you have done?" The woman said, "The serpent tricked me, and I ate."
01â 3:14 The LORD God said to the serpent, "Because you have done this, cursed are you among all animals and among all wild creatures; upon your belly you shall go, and dust you shall eat all the days of your life.
01â 3:15 I will put enmity between you and the woman, and between your offspring and hers; he will strike your head, and you will strike his heel."
01â 3:16 To the woman he said, "I will greatly increase your pangs in childbearing; in pain you shall bring forth children, yet your desire shall be for your husband, and he shall rule over you."
01â 3:17 And to the man he said, "Because you have listened to the voice of your wife, and have eaten of the tree about which I commanded you, 'You shall not eat of it,' cursed is the ground because of you; in toil you shall eat of it all the days of your life;
01â 3:18 thorns and thistles it shall bring forth for you; and you shall eat the plants of the field.
01â 3:19 By the sweat of your face you shall eat bread until you return to the ground, for out of it you were taken; you are dust, and to dust you shall return."
01â 3:20 The man named his wife Eve, because she was the mother of all living.
01â 3:21 And the LORD God made garments of skins for the man and for his wife, and clothed them.
01â 3:22 Then the LORD God said, "See, the man has become like one of us, knowing good and evil; and now, he might reach out his hand and take also from the tree of life, and eat, and live forever"--
01â 3:23 therefore the LORD God sent him forth from the garden of Eden, to till the ground from which he was taken.
01â 3:24 He drove out the man; and at the east of the garden of Eden he placed the cherubim, and a sword flaming and turning to guard the way to the tree of life.
01â 4:1 Now the man knew his wife Eve, and she conceived and bore Cain, saying, "I have produced a man with the help of the LORD."
01â 4:2 Next she bore his brother Abel. Now Abel was a keeper of sheep, and Cain a tiller of the ground.
01â 4:3 In the course of time Cain brought to the LORD an offering of the fruit of the ground,
01â 4:4 and Abel for his part brought of the firstlings of his flock, their fat portions. And the LORD had regard for Abel and his offering,
01â 4:5 but for Cain and his offering he had no regard. So Cain was very angry, and his countenance fell.
01â 4:6 The LORD said to Cain, "Why are you angry, and why has your countenance fallen?
01â 4:7 If you do well, will you not be accepted? And if you do not do well, sin is lurking at the door; its desire is for you, but you must master it."
01â 4:8 Cain said to his brother Abel, "Let us go out to the field." And when they were in the field, Cain rose up against his brother Abel, and killed him.
01â 4:9 Then the LORD said to Cain, "Where is your brother Abel?" He said, "I do not know; am I my brother's keeper?"
01â 4:10 And the LORD said, "What have you done? Listen; your brother's blood is crying out to me from the ground!
01â 4:11 And now you are cursed from the ground, which has opened its mouth to receive your brother's blood from your hand.
01â 4:12 When you till the ground, it will no longer yield to you its strength; you will be a fugitive and a wanderer on the earth."
01â 4:13 Cain said to the LORD, "My punishment is greater than I can bear!
01â 4:14 Today you have driven me away from the soil, and I shall be hidden from your face; I shall be a fugitive and a wanderer on the earth, and anyone who meets me may kill me."
01â 4:15 Then the LORD said to him, "Not so! Whoever kills Cain will suffer a sevenfold vengeance." And the LORD put a mark on Cain, so that no one who came upon him would kill him.
01â 4:16 Then Cain went away from the presence of the LORD, and settled in the land of Nod, east of Eden.
01â 4:17 Cain knew his wife, and she conceived and bore Enoch; and he built a city, and named it Enoch after his son Enoch.
01â 4:18 To Enoch was born Irad; and Irad was the father of Mehujael, and Mehujael the father of Methushael, and Methushael the father of Lamech.
01â 4:19 Lamech took two wives; the name of the one was Adah, and the name of the other Zillah.
01â 4:20 Adah bore Jabal; he was the ancestor of those who live in tents and have livestock.
01â 4:21 His brother's name was Jubal; he was the ancestor of all those who play the lyre and pipe.
01â 4:22 Zillah bore Tubal-cain, who made all kinds of bronze and iron tools. The sister of Tubal-cain was Naamah.
01â 4:23 Lamech said to his wives: "Adah and Zillah, hear my voice; you wives of Lamech, listen to what I say: I have killed a man for wounding me, a young man for striking me.
01â 4:24 If Cain is avenged sevenfold, truly Lamech seventy-sevenfold."
01â 4:25 Adam knew his wife again, and she bore a son and named him Seth, for she said, "God has appointed for me another child instead of Abel, because Cain killed him."
01â 4:26 To Seth also a son was born, and he named him Enosh. At that time people began to invoke the name of the LORD.
01â 5:1 This is the list of the descendants of Adam. When God created humankind, he made them in the likeness of God.
01â 5:2 Male and female he created them, and he blessed them and named them "Humankind" when they were created.
01â 5:3 When Adam had lived one hundred thirty years, he became the father of a son in his likeness, according to his image, and named him Seth.
01â 5:4 The days of Adam after he became the father of Seth were eight hundred years; and he had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:5 Thus all the days that Adam lived were nine hundred thirty years; and he died.
01â 5:6 When Seth had lived one hundred five years, he became the father of Enosh.
01â 5:7 Seth lived after the birth of Enosh eight hundred seven years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:8 Thus all the days of Seth were nine hundred twelve years; and he died.
01â 5:9 When Enosh had lived ninety years, he became the father of Kenan.
01â 5:10 Enosh lived after the birth of Kenan eight hundred fifteen years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:11 Thus all the days of Enosh were nine hundred five years; and he died.
01â 5:12 When Kenan had lived seventy years, he became the father of Mahalalel.
01â 5:13 Kenan lived after the birth of Mahalalel eight hundred and forty years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:14 Thus all the days of Kenan were nine hundred and ten years; and he died.
01â 5:15 When Mahalalel had lived sixty-five years, he became the father of Jared.
01â 5:16 Mahalalel lived after the birth of Jared eight hundred thirty years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:17 Thus all the days of Mahalalel were eight hundred ninety-five years; and he died.
01â 5:18 When Jared had lived one hundred sixty-two years he became the father of Enoch.
01â 5:19 Jared lived after the birth of Enoch eight hundred years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:20 Thus all the days of Jared were nine hundred sixty-two years; and he died.
01â 5:21 When Enoch had lived sixty-five years, he became the father of Methuselah.
01â 5:22 Enoch walked with God after the birth of Methuselah three hundred years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:23 Thus all the days of Enoch were three hundred sixty-five years.
01â 5:24 Enoch walked with God; then he was no more, because God took him.
01â 5:25 When Methuselah had lived one hundred eighty-seven years, he became the father of Lamech.
01â 5:26 Methuselah lived after the birth of Lamech seven hundred eighty-two years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:27 Thus all the days of Methuselah were nine hundred sixty-nine years; and he died.
01â 5:28 When Lamech had lived one hundred eighty-two years, he became the father of a son;
01â 5:29 he named him Noah, saying, "Out of the ground that the LORD has cursed this one shall bring us relief from our work and from the toil of our hands."
01â 5:30 Lamech lived after the birth of Noah five hundred ninety-five years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 5:31 Thus all the days of Lamech were seven hundred seventy-seven years; and he died.
01â 5:32 After Noah was five hundred years old, Noah became the father of Shem, Ham, and Japheth.
01â 6:1 When people began to multiply on the face of the ground, and daughters were born to them,
01â 6:2 the sons of God saw that they were fair; and they took wives for themselves of all that they chose.
01â 6:3 Then the LORD said, "My spirit shall not abide in mortals forever, for they are flesh; their days shall be one hundred twenty years."
01â 6:4 The Nephilim were on the earth in those days--and also afterward--when the sons of God went in to the daughters of humans, who bore children to them. These were the heroes that were of old, warriors of renown.
01â 6:5 The LORD saw that the wickedness of humankind was great in the earth, and that every inclination of the thoughts of their hearts was only evil continually.
01â 6:6 And the LORD was sorry that he had made humankind on the earth, and it grieved him to his heart.
01â 6:7 So the LORD said, "I will blot out from the earth the human beings I have created--people together with animals and creeping things and birds of the air, for I am sorry that I have made them."
01â 6:8 But Noah found favor in the sight of the LORD.
01â 6:9 These are the descendants of Noah. Noah was a righteous man, blameless in his generation; Noah walked with God.
01â 6:10 And Noah had three sons, Shem, Ham, and Japheth.
01â 6:11 Now the earth was corrupt in God's sight, and the earth was filled with violence.
01â 6:12 And God saw that the earth was corrupt; for all flesh had corrupted its ways upon the earth.
01â 6:13 And God said to Noah, "I have determined to make an end of all flesh, for the earth is filled with violence because of them; now I am going to destroy them along with the earth.
01â 6:14 Make yourself an ark of cypress wood; make rooms in the ark, and cover it inside and out with pitch.
01â 6:15 This is how you are to make it: the length of the ark three hundred cubits, its width fifty cubits, and its height thirty cubits.
01â 6:16 Make a roof for the ark, and finish it to a cubit above; and put the door of the ark in its side; make it with lower, second, and third decks.
01â 6:17 For my part, I am going to bring a flood of waters on the earth, to destroy from under heaven all flesh in which is the breath of life; everything that is on the earth shall die.
01â 6:18 But I will establish my covenant with you; and you shall come into the ark, you, your sons, your wife, and your sons' wives with you.
01â 6:19 And of every living thing, of all flesh, you shall bring two of every kind into the ark, to keep them alive with you; they shall be male and female.
01â 6:20 Of the birds according to their kinds, and of the animals according to their kinds, of every creeping thing of the ground according to its kind, two of every kind shall come in to you, to keep them alive.
01â 6:21 Also take with you every kind of food that is eaten, and store it up; and it shall serve as food for you and for them."
01â 6:22 Noah did this; he did all that God commanded him.
01â 7:1 Then the LORD said to Noah, "Go into the ark, you and all your household, for I have seen that you alone are righteous before me in this generation.
01â 7:2 Take with you seven pairs of all clean animals, the male and its mate; and a pair of the animals that are not clean, the male and its mate;
01â 7:3 and seven pairs of the birds of the air also, male and female, to keep their kind alive on the face of all the earth.
01â 7:4 For in seven days I will send rain on the earth for forty days and forty nights; and every living thing that I have made I will blot out from the face of the ground."
01â 7:5 And Noah did all that the LORD had commanded him.
01â 7:6 Noah was six hundred years old when the flood of waters came on the earth.
01â 7:7 And Noah with his sons and his wife and his sons' wives went into the ark to escape the waters of the flood.
01â 7:8 Of clean animals, and of animals that are not clean, and of birds, and of everything that creeps on the ground,
01â 7:9 two and two, male and female, went into the ark with Noah, as God had commanded Noah.
01â 7:10 And after seven days the waters of the flood came on the earth.
01â 7:11 In the six hundredth year of Noah's life, in the second month, on the seventeenth day of the month, on that day all the fountains of the great deep burst forth, and the windows of the heavens were opened.
01â 7:12 The rain fell on the earth forty days and forty nights.
01â 7:13 On the very same day Noah with his sons, Shem and Ham and Japheth, and Noah's wife and the three wives of his sons entered the ark,
01â 7:14 they and every wild animal of every kind, and all domestic animals of every kind, and every creeping thing that creeps on the earth, and every bird of every kind--every bird, every winged creature.
01â 7:15 They went into the ark with Noah, two and two of all flesh in which there was the breath of life.
01â 7:16 And those that entered, male and female of all flesh, went in as God had commanded him; and the LORD shut him in.
01â 7:17 The flood continued forty days on the earth; and the waters increased, and bore up the ark, and it rose high above the earth.
01â 7:18 The waters swelled and increased greatly on the earth; and the ark floated on the face of the waters.
01â 7:19 The waters swelled so mightily on the earth that all the high mountains under the whole heaven were covered;
01â 7:20 the waters swelled above the mountains, covering them fifteen cubits deep.
01â 7:21 And all flesh died that moved on the earth, birds, domestic animals, wild animals, all swarming creatures that swarm on the earth, and all human beings;
01â 7:22 everything on dry land in whose nostrils was the breath of life died.
01â 7:23 He blotted out every living thing that was on the face of the ground, human beings and animals and creeping things and birds of the air; they were blotted out from the earth. Only Noah was left, and those that were with him in the ark.
01â 7:24 And the waters swelled on the earth for one hundred fifty days.
01â 8:1 But God remembered Noah and all the wild animals and all the domestic animals that were with him in the ark. And God made a wind blow over the earth, and the waters subsided;
01â 8:2 the fountains of the deep and the windows of the heavens were closed, the rain from the heavens was restrained,
01â 8:3 and the waters gradually receded from the earth. At the end of one hundred fifty days the waters had abated;
01â 8:4 and in the seventh month, on the seventeenth day of the month, the ark came to rest on the mountains of Ararat.
01â 8:5 The waters continued to abate until the tenth month; in the tenth month, on the first day of the month, the tops of the mountains appeared.
01â 8:6 At the end of forty days Noah opened the window of the ark that he had made
01â 8:7 and sent out the raven; and it went to and fro until the waters were dried up from the earth.
01â 8:8 Then he sent out the dove from him, to see if the waters had subsided from the face of the ground;
01â 8:9 but the dove found no place to set its foot, and it returned to him to the ark, for the waters were still on the face of the whole earth. So he put out his hand and took it and brought it into the ark with him.
01â 8:10 He waited another seven days, and again he sent out the dove from the ark;
01â 8:11 and the dove came back to him in the evening, and there in its beak was a freshly plucked olive leaf; so Noah knew that the waters had subsided from the earth.
01â 8:12 Then he waited another seven days, and sent out the dove; and it did not return to him any more.
01â 8:13 In the six hundred first year, in the first month, the first day of the month, the waters were dried up from the earth; and Noah removed the covering of the ark, and looked, and saw that the face of the ground was drying.
01â 8:14 In the second month, on the twenty-seventh day of the month, the earth was dry.
01â 8:15 Then God said to Noah,
01â 8:16 "Go out of the ark, you and your wife, and your sons and your sons' wives with you.
01â 8:17 Bring out with you every living thing that is with you of all flesh--birds and animals and every creeping thing that creeps on the earth--so that they may abound on the earth, and be fruitful and multiply on the earth."
01â 8:18 So Noah went out with his sons and his wife and his sons' wives.
01â 8:19 And every animal, every creeping thing, and every bird, everything that moves on the earth, went out of the ark by families.
01â 8:20 Then Noah built an altar to the LORD, and took of every clean animal and of every clean bird, and offered burnt offerings on the altar.
01â 8:21 And when the LORD smelled the pleasing odor, the LORD said in his heart, "I will never again curse the ground because of humankind, for the inclination of the human heart is evil from youth; nor will I ever again destroy every living creature as I have done.
01â 8:22 As long as the earth endures, seedtime and harvest, cold and heat, summer and winter, day and night, shall not cease."
01â 9:1 God blessed Noah and his sons, and said to them, "Be fruitful and multiply, and fill the earth.
01â 9:2 The fear and dread of you shall rest on every animal of the earth, and on every bird of the air, on everything that creeps on the ground, and on all the fish of the sea; into your hand they are delivered.
01â 9:3 Every moving thing that lives shall be food for you; and just as I gave you the green plants, I give you everything.
01â 9:4 Only, you shall not eat flesh with its life, that is, its blood.
01â 9:5 For your own lifeblood I will surely require a reckoning: from every animal I will require it and from human beings, each one for the blood of another, I will require a reckoning for human life.
01â 9:6 Whoever sheds the blood of a human, by a human shall that person's blood be shed; for in his own image God made humankind.
01â 9:7 And you, be fruitful and multiply, abound on the earth and multiply in it."
01â 9:8 Then God said to Noah and to his sons with him,
01â 9:9 "As for me, I am establishing my covenant with you and your descendants after you,
01â 9:10 and with every living creature that is with you, the birds, the domestic animals, and every animal of the earth with you, as many as came out of the ark.
01â 9:11 I establish my covenant with you, that never again shall all flesh be cut off by the waters of a flood, and never again shall there be a flood to destroy the earth."
01â 9:12 God said, "This is the sign of the covenant that I make between me and you and every living creature that is with you, for all future generations:
01â 9:13 I have set my bow in the clouds, and it shall be a sign of the covenant between me and the earth.
01â 9:14 When I bring clouds over the earth and the bow is seen in the clouds,
01â 9:15 I will remember my covenant that is between me and you and every living creature of all flesh; and the waters shall never again become a flood to destroy all flesh.
01â 9:16 When the bow is in the clouds, I will see it and remember the everlasting covenant between God and every living creature of all flesh that is on the earth."
01â 9:17 God said to Noah, "This is the sign of the covenant that I have established between me and all flesh that is on the earth."
01â 9:18 The sons of Noah who went out of the ark were Shem, Ham, and Japheth. Ham was the father of Canaan.
01â 9:19 These three were the sons of Noah; and from these the whole earth was peopled.
01â 9:20 Noah, a man of the soil, was the first to plant a vineyard.
01â 9:21 He drank some of the wine and became drunk, and he lay uncovered in his tent.
01â 9:22 And Ham, the father of Canaan, saw the nakedness of his father, and told his two brothers outside.
01â 9:23 Then Shem and Japheth took a garment, laid it on both their shoulders, and walked backward and covered the nakedness of their father; their faces were turned away, and they did not see their father's nakedness.
01â 9:24 When Noah awoke from his wine and knew what his youngest son had done to him,
01â 9:25 he said, "Cursed be Canaan; lowest of slaves shall he be to his brothers."
01â 9:26 He also said, "Blessed by the LORD my God be Shem; and let Canaan be his slave.
01â 9:27 May God make space for Japheth, and let him live in the tents of Shem; and let Canaan be his slave."
01â 9:28 After the flood Noah lived three hundred fifty years.
01â 9:29 All the days of Noah were nine hundred fifty years; and he died.
01â 10:1 These are the descendants of Noah's sons, Shem, Ham, and Japheth; children were born to them after the flood.
01â 10:2 The descendants of Japheth: Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal, Meshech, and Tiras.
01â 10:3 The descendants of Gomer: Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.
01â 10:4 The descendants of Javan: Elishah, Tarshish, Kittim, and Rodanim.
01â 10:5 From these the coastland peoples spread. These are the descendants of Japheth in their lands, with their own language, by their families, in their nations.
01â 10:6 The descendants of Ham: Cush, Egypt, Put, and Canaan.
01â 10:7 The descendants of Cush: Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca. The descendants of Raamah: Sheba and Dedan.
01â 10:8 Cush became the father of Nimrod; he was the first on earth to become a mighty warrior.
01â 10:9 He was a mighty hunter before the LORD; therefore it is said, "Like Nimrod a mighty hunter before the LORD."
01â 10:10 The beginning of his kingdom was Babel, Erech, and Accad, all of them in the land of Shinar.
01â 10:11 From that land he went into Assyria, and built Nineveh, Rehoboth-ir, Calah, and
01â 10:12 Resen between Nineveh and Calah; that is the great city.
01â 10:13 Egypt became the father of Ludim, Anamim, Lehabim, Naphtuhim,
01â 10:14 Pathrusim, Casluhim, and Caphtorim, from which the Philistines come.
01â 10:15 Canaan became the father of Sidon his firstborn, and Heth,
01â 10:16 and the Jebusites, the Amorites, the Girgashites,
01â 10:17 the Hivites, the Arkites, the Sinites,
01â 10:18 the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites. Afterward the families of the Canaanites spread abroad.
01â 10:19 And the territory of the Canaanites extended from Sidon, in the direction of Gerar, as far as Gaza, and in the direction of Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, and Zeboiim, as far as Lasha.
01â 10:20 These are the descendants of Ham, by their families, their languages, their lands, and their nations.
01â 10:21 To Shem also, the father of all the children of Eber, the elder brother of Japheth, children were born.
01â 10:22 The descendants of Shem: Elam, Asshur, Arpachshad, Lud, and Aram.
01â 10:23 The descendants of Aram: Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.
01â 10:24 Arpachshad became the father of Shelah; and Shelah became the father of Eber.
01â 10:25 To Eber were born two sons: the name of the one was Peleg, for in his days the earth was divided, and his brother's name was Joktan.
01â 10:26 Joktan became the father of Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah,
01â 10:27 Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah,
01â 10:28 Obal, Abimael, Sheba,
01â 10:29 Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab; all these were the descendants of Joktan.
01â 10:30 The territory in which they lived extended from Mesha in the direction of Sephar, the hill country of the east.
01â 10:31 These are the descendants of Shem, by their families, their languages, their lands, and their nations.
01â 10:32 These are the families of Noah's sons, according to their genealogies, in their nations; and from these the nations spread abroad on the earth after the flood.
01â 11:1 Now the whole earth had one language and the same words.
01â 11:2 And as they migrated from the east, they came upon a plain in the land of Shinar and settled there.
01â 11:3 And they said to one another, "Come, let us make bricks, and burn them thoroughly." And they had brick for stone, and bitumen for mortar.
01â 11:4 Then they said, "Come, let us build ourselves a city, and a tower with its top in the heavens, and let us make a name for ourselves; otherwise we shall be scattered abroad upon the face of the whole earth."
01â 11:5 The LORD came down to see the city and the tower, which mortals had built.
01â 11:6 And the LORD said, "Look, they are one people, and they have all one language; and this is only the beginning of what they will do; nothing that they propose to do will now be impossible for them.
01â 11:7 Come, let us go down, and confuse their language there, so that they will not understand one another's speech."
01â 11:8 So the LORD scattered them abroad from there over the face of all the earth, and they left off building the city.
01â 11:9 Therefore it was called Babel, because there the LORD confused the language of all the earth; and from there the LORD scattered them abroad over the face of all the earth.
01â 11:10 These are the descendants of Shem. When Shem was one hundred years old, he became the father of Arpachshad two years after the flood;
01â 11:11 and Shem lived after the birth of Arpachshad five hundred years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:12 When Arpachshad had lived thirty-five years, he became the father of Shelah;
01â 11:13 and Arpachshad lived after the birth of Shelah four hundred three years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:14 When Shelah had lived thirty years, he became the father of Eber;
01â 11:15 and Shelah lived after the birth of Eber four hundred three years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:16 When Eber had lived thirty-four years, he became the father of Peleg;
01â 11:17 and Eber lived after the birth of Peleg four hundred thirty years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:18 When Peleg had lived thirty years, he became the father of Reu;
01â 11:19 and Peleg lived after the birth of Reu two hundred nine years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:20 When Reu had lived thirty-two years, he became the father of Serug;
01â 11:21 and Reu lived after the birth of Serug two hundred seven years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:22 When Serug had lived thirty years, he became the father of Nahor;
01â 11:23 and Serug lived after the birth of Nahor two hundred years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:24 When Nahor had lived twenty-nine years, he became the father of Terah;
01â 11:25 and Nahor lived after the birth of Terah one hundred nineteen years, and had other sons and daughters.
01â 11:26 When Terah had lived seventy years, he became the father of Abram, Nahor, and Haran.
01â 11:27 Now these are the descendants of Terah. Terah was the father of Abram, Nahor, and Haran; and Haran was the father of Lot.
01â 11:28 Haran died before his father Terah in the land of his birth, in Ur of the Chaldeans.
01â 11:29 Abram and Nahor took wives; the name of Abram's wife was Sarai, and the name of Nahor's wife was Milcah. She was the daughter of Haran the father of Milcah and Iscah.
01â 11:30 Now Sarai was barren; she had no child.
01â 11:31 Terah took his son Abram and his grandson Lot son of Haran, and his daughter-in-law Sarai, his son Abram's wife, and they went out together from Ur of the Chaldeans to go into the land of Canaan; but when they came to Haran, they settled there.
01â 11:32 The days of Terah were two hundred five years; and Terah died in Haran.
01â 12:1 Now the LORD said to Abram, "Go from your country and your kindred and your father's house to the land that I will show you.
01â 12:2 I will make of you a great nation, and I will bless you, and make your name great, so that you will be a blessing.
01â 12:3 I will bless those who bless you, and the one who curses you I will curse; and in you all the families of the earth shall be blessed."
01â 12:4 So Abram went, as the LORD had told him; and Lot went with him. Abram was seventy-five years old when he departed from Haran.
01â 12:5 Abram took his wife Sarai and his brother's son Lot, and all the possessions that they had gathered, and the persons whom they had acquired in Haran; and they set forth to go to the land of Canaan. When they had come to the land of Canaan,
01â 12:6 Abram passed through the land to the place at Shechem, to the oak of Moreh. At that time the Canaanites were in the land.
01â 12:7 Then the LORD appeared to Abram, and said, "To your offspring I will give this land." So he built there an altar to the LORD, who had appeared to him.
01â 12:8 From there he moved on to the hill country on the east of Bethel, and pitched his tent, with Bethel on the west and Ai on the east; and there he built an altar to the LORD and invoked the name of the LORD.
01â 12:9 And Abram journeyed on by stages toward the Negeb.
01â 12:10 Now there was a famine in the land. So Abram went down to Egypt to reside there as an alien, for the famine was severe in the land.
01â 12:11 When he was about to enter Egypt, he said to his wife Sarai, "I know well that you are a woman beautiful in appearance;
01â 12:12 and when the Egyptians see you, they will say, 'This is his wife'; then they will kill me, but they will let you live.
01â 12:13 Say you are my sister, so that it may go well with me because of you, and that my life may be spared on your account."
01â 12:14 When Abram entered Egypt the Egyptians saw that the woman was very beautiful.
01â 12:15 When the officials of Pharaoh saw her, they praised her to Pharaoh. And the woman was taken into Pharaoh's house.
01â 12:16 And for her sake he dealt well with Abram; and he had sheep, oxen, male donkeys, male and female slaves, female donkeys, and camels.
01â 12:17 But the LORD afflicted Pharaoh and his house with great plagues because of Sarai, Abram's wife.
01â 12:18 So Pharaoh called Abram, and said, "What is this you have done to me? Why did you not tell me that she was your wife?
01â 12:19 Why did you say, 'She is my sister,' so that I took her for my wife? Now then, here is your wife, take her, and be gone."
01â 12:20 And Pharaoh gave his men orders concerning him; and they set him on the way, with his wife and all that he had.
01â 13:1 So Abram went up from Egypt, he and his wife, and all that he had, and Lot with him, into the Negeb.
01â 13:2 Now Abram was very rich in livestock, in silver, and in gold.
01â 13:3 He journeyed on by stages from the Negeb as far as Bethel, to the place where his tent had been at the beginning, between Bethel and Ai,
01â 13:4 to the place where he had made an altar at the first; and there Abram called on the name of the LORD.
01â 13:5 Now Lot, who went with Abram, also had flocks and herds and tents,
01â 13:6 so that the land could not support both of them living together; for their possessions were so great that they could not live together,
01â 13:7 and there was strife between the herders of Abram's livestock and the herders of Lot's livestock. At that time the Canaanites and the Perizzites lived in the land.
01â 13:8 Then Abram said to Lot, "Let there be no strife between you and me, and between your herders and my herders; for we are kindred.
01â 13:9 Is not the whole land before you? Separate yourself from me. If you take the left hand, then I will go to the right; or if you take the right hand, then I will go to the left."
01â 13:10 Lot looked about him, and saw that the plain of the Jordan was well watered everywhere like the garden of the LORD, like the land of Egypt, in the direction of Zoar; this was before the LORD had destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah.
01â 13:11 So Lot chose for himself all the plain of the Jordan, and Lot journeyed eastward; thus they separated from each other.
01â 13:12 Abram settled in the land of Canaan, while Lot settled among the cities of the Plain and moved his tent as far as Sodom.
01â 13:13 Now the people of Sodom were wicked, great sinners against the LORD.
01â 13:14 The LORD said to Abram, after Lot had separated from him, "Raise your eyes now, and look from the place where you are, northward and southward and eastward and westward;
01â 13:15 for all the land that you see I will give to you and to your offspring forever.
01â 13:16 I will make your offspring like the dust of the earth; so that if one can count the dust of the earth, your offspring also can be counted.
01â 13:17 Rise up, walk through the length and the breadth of the land, for I will give it to you."
01â 13:18 So Abram moved his tent, and came and settled by the oaks of Mamre, which are at Hebron; and there he built an altar to the LORD.
01â 14:1 In the days of King Amraphel of Shinar, King Arioch of Ellasar, King Chedorlaomer of Elam, and King Tidal of Goiim,
01â 14:2 these kings made war with King Bera of Sodom, King Birsha of Gomorrah, King Shinab of Admah, King Shemeber of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar).
01â 14:3 All these joined forces in the Valley of Siddim (that is, the Dead Sea).
01â 14:4 Twelve years they had served Chedorlaomer, but in the thirteenth year they rebelled.
01â 14:5 In the fourteenth year Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with him came and subdued the Rephaim in Ashteroth-karnaim, the Zuzim in Ham, the Emim in Shaveh-kiriathaim,
01â 14:6 and the Horites in the hill country of Seir as far as El-paran on the edge of the wilderness;
01â 14:7 then they turned back and came to En-mishpat (that is, Kadesh), and subdued all the country of the Amalekites, and also the Amorites who lived in Hazazon-tamar.
01â 14:8 Then the king of Sodom, the king of Gomorrah, the king of Admah, the king of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (that is, Zoar) went out, and they joined battle in the Valley of Siddim
01â 14:9 with King Chedorlaomer of Elam, King Tidal of Goiim, King Amraphel of Shinar, and King Arioch of Ellasar, four kings against five.
01â 14:10 Now the Valley of Siddim was full of bitumen pits; and as the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah fled, some fell into them, and the rest fled to the hill country.
01â 14:11 So the enemy took all the goods of Sodom and Gomorrah, and all their provisions, and went their way;
01â 14:12 they also took Lot, the son of Abram's brother, who lived in Sodom, and his goods, and departed.
01â 14:13 Then one who had escaped came and told Abram the Hebrew, who was living by the oaks of Mamre the Amorite, brother of Eshcol and of Aner; these were allies of Abram.
01â 14:14 When Abram heard that his nephew had been taken captive, he led forth his trained men, born in his house, three hundred eighteen of them, and went in pursuit as far as Dan.
01â 14:15 He divided his forces against them by night, he and his servants, and routed them and pursued them to Hobah, north of Damascus.
01â 14:16 Then he brought back all the goods, and also brought back his nephew Lot with his goods, and the women and the people.
01â 14:17 After his return from the defeat of Chedorlaomer and the kings who were with him, the king of Sodom went out to meet him at the Valley of Shaveh (that is, the King's Valley).
01â 14:18 And King Melchizedek of Salem brought out bread and wine; he was priest of God Most High.
01â 14:19 He blessed him and said, "Blessed be Abram by God Most High, maker of heaven and earth;
01â 14:20 and blessed be God Most High, who has delivered your enemies into your hand!" And Abram gave him one tenth of everything.
01â 14:21 Then the king of Sodom said to Abram, "Give me the persons, but take the goods for yourself."
01â 14:22 But Abram said to the king of Sodom, "I have sworn to the LORD, God Most High, maker of heaven and earth,
01â 14:23 that I would not take a thread or a sandal-thong or anything that is yours, so that you might not say, 'I have made Abram rich.'
01â 14:24 I will take nothing but what the young men have eaten, and the share of the men who went with me--Aner, Eshcol, and Mamre. Let them take their share."
01â 15:1 After these things the word of the LORD came to Abram in a vision, "Do not be afraid, Abram, I am your shield; your reward shall be very great."
01â 15:2 But Abram said, "O Lord GOD, what will you give me, for I continue childless, and the heir of my house is Eliezer of Damascus?"
01â 15:3 And Abram said, "You have given me no offspring, and so a slave born in my house is to be my heir."
01â 15:4 But the word of the LORD came to him, "This man shall not be your heir; no one but your very own issue shall be your heir."
01â 15:5 He brought him outside and said, "Look toward heaven and count the stars, if you are able to count them." Then he said to him, "So shall your descendants be."
01â 15:6 And he believed the LORD; and the LORD reckoned it to him as righteousness.
01â 15:7 Then he said to him, "I am the LORD who brought you from Ur of the Chaldeans, to give you this land to possess."
01â 15:8 But he said, "O Lord GOD, how am I to know that I shall possess it?"
01â 15:9 He said to him, "Bring me a heifer three years old, a female goat three years old, a ram three years old, a turtledove, and a young pigeon."
01â 15:10 He brought him all these and cut them in two, laying each half over against the other; but he did not cut the birds in two.
01â 15:11 And when birds of prey came down on the carcasses, Abram drove them away.
01â 15:12 As the sun was going down, a deep sleep fell upon Abram, and a deep and terrifying darkness descended upon him.
01â 15:13 Then the LORD said to Abram, "Know this for certain, that your offspring shall be aliens in a land that is not theirs, and shall be slaves there, and they shall be oppressed for four hundred years;
01â 15:14 but I will bring judgment on the nation that they serve, and afterward they shall come out with great possessions.
01â 15:15 As for yourself, you shall go to your ancestors in peace; you shall be buried in a good old age.
01â 15:16 And they shall come back here in the fourth generation; for the iniquity of the Amorites is not yet complete."
01â 15:17 When the sun had gone down and it was dark, a smoking fire pot and a flaming torch passed between these pieces.
01â 15:18 On that day the LORD made a covenant with Abram, saying, "To your descendants I give this land, from the river of Egypt to the great river, the river Euphrates,
01â 15:19 the land of the Kenites, the Kenizzites, the Kadmonites,
01â 15:20 the Hittites, the Perizzites, the Rephaim,
01â 15:21 the Amorites, the Canaanites, the Girgashites, and the Jebusites."
01â 16:1 Now Sarai, Abram's wife, bore him no children. She had an Egyptian slave-girl whose name was Hagar,
01â 16:2 and Sarai said to Abram, "You see that the LORD has prevented me from bearing children; go in to my slave-girl; it may be that I shall obtain children by her." And Abram listened to the voice of Sarai.
01â 16:3 So, after Abram had lived ten years in the land of Canaan, Sarai, Abram's wife, took Hagar the Egyptian, her slave-girl, and gave her to her husband Abram as a wife.
01â 16:4 He went in to Hagar, and she conceived; and when she saw that she had conceived, she looked with contempt on her mistress.
01â 16:5 Then Sarai said to Abram, "May the wrong done to me be on you! I gave my slave-girl to your embrace, and when she saw that she had conceived, she looked on me with contempt. May the LORD judge between you and me!"
01â 16:6 But Abram said to Sarai, "Your slave-girl is in your power; do to her as you please." Then Sarai dealt harshly with her, and she ran away from her.
01â 16:7 The angel of the LORD found her by a spring of water in the wilderness, the spring on the way to Shur.
01â 16:8 And he said, "Hagar, slave-girl of Sarai, where have you come from and where are you going?" She said, "I am running away from my mistress Sarai."
01â 16:9 The angel of the LORD said to her, "Return to your mistress, and submit to her."
01â 16:10 The angel of the LORD also said to her, "I will so greatly multiply your offspring that they cannot be counted for multitude."
01â 16:11 And the angel of the LORD said to her, "Now you have conceived and shall bear a son; you shall call him Ishmael, for the LORD has given heed to your affliction.
01â 16:12 He shall be a wild ass of a man, with his hand against everyone, and everyone's hand against him; and he shall live at odds with all his kin."
01â 16:13 So she named the LORD who spoke to her, "You are El-roi"; for she said, "Have I really seen God and remained alive after seeing him?"
01â 16:14 Therefore the well was called Beer-lahai-roi; it lies between Kadesh and Bered.
01â 16:15 Hagar bore Abram a son; and Abram named his son, whom Hagar bore, Ishmael.
01â 16:16 Abram was eighty-six years old when Hagar bore him Ishmael.
01â 17:1 When Abram was ninety-nine years old, the LORD appeared to Abram, and said to him, "I am God Almighty; walk before me, and be blameless.
01â 17:2 And I will make my covenant between me and you, and will make you exceedingly numerous."
01â 17:3 Then Abram fell on his face; and God said to him,
01â 17:4 "As for me, this is my covenant with you: You shall be the ancestor of a multitude of nations.
01â 17:5 No longer shall your name be Abram, but your name shall be Abraham; for I have made you the ancestor of a multitude of nations.
01â 17:6 I will make you exceedingly fruitful; and I will make nations of you, and kings shall come from you.
01â 17:7 I will establish my covenant between me and you, and your offspring after you throughout their generations, for an everlasting covenant, to be God to you and to your offspring after you.
01â 17:8 And I will give to you, and to your offspring after you, the land where you are now an alien, all the land of Canaan, for a perpetual holding; and I will be their God."
01â 17:9 God said to Abraham, "As for you, you shall keep my covenant, you and your offspring after you throughout their generations.
01â 17:10 This is my covenant, which you shall keep, between me and you and your offspring after you: Every male among you shall be circumcised.
01â 17:11 You shall circumcise the flesh of your foreskins, and it shall be a sign of the covenant between me and you.
01â 17:12 Throughout your generations every male among you shall be circumcised when he is eight days old, including the slave born in your house and the one bought with your money from any foreigner who is not of your offspring.
01â 17:13 Both the slave born in your house and the one bought with your money must be circumcised. So shall my covenant be in your flesh an everlasting covenant.
01â 17:14 Any uncircumcised male who is not circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin shall be cut off from his people; he has broken my covenant."
01â 17:15 God said to Abraham, "As for Sarah your wife, you shall not call her Sarai, but Sarah shall be her name.
01â 17:16 I will bless her, and moreover I will give you a son by her. I will bless her, and she shall give rise to nations; kings of peoples shall come from her."
01â 17:17 Then Abraham fell on his face and laughed, and said to himself, "Can a child be born to a man who is a hundred years old? Can Sarah, who is ninety years old, bear a child?"
01â 17:18 And Abraham said to God, "O that Ishmael might live in your sight!"
01â 17:19 God said, "No, but your wife Sarah shall bear you a son, and you shall name him Isaac. I will establish my covenant with him as an everlasting covenant for his offspring after him.
01â 17:20 As for Ishmael, I have heard you; I will bless him and make him fruitful and exceedingly numerous; he shall be the father of twelve princes, and I will make him a great nation.
01â 17:21 But my covenant I will establish with Isaac, whom Sarah shall bear to you at this season next year."
01â 17:22 And when he had finished talking with him, God went up from Abraham.
01â 17:23 Then Abraham took his son Ishmael and all the slaves born in his house or bought with his money, every male among the men of Abraham's house, and he circumcised the flesh of their foreskins that very day, as God had said to him.
01â 17:24 Abraham was ninety-nine years old when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin.
01â 17:25 And his son Ishmael was thirteen years old when he was circumcised in the flesh of his foreskin.
01â 17:26 That very day Abraham and his son Ishmael were circumcised;
01â 17:27 and all the men of his house, slaves born in the house and those bought with money from a foreigner, were circumcised with him.
01â 18:1 The LORD appeared to Abraham by the oaks of Mamre, as he sat at the entrance of his tent in the heat of the day.
01â 18:2 He looked up and saw three men standing near him. When he saw them, he ran from the tent entrance to meet them, and bowed down to the ground.
01â 18:3 He said, "My lord, if I find favor with you, do not pass by your servant.
01â 18:4 Let a little water be brought, and wash your feet, and rest yourselves under the tree.
01â 18:5 Let me bring a little bread, that you may refresh yourselves, and after that you may pass on--since you have come to your servant." So they said, "Do as you have said."
01â 18:6 And Abraham hastened into the tent to Sarah, and said, "Make ready quickly three measures of choice flour, knead it, and make cakes."
01â 18:7 Abraham ran to the herd, and took a calf, tender and good, and gave it to the servant, who hastened to prepare it.
01â 18:8 Then he took curds and milk and the calf that he had prepared, and set it before them; and he stood by them under the tree while they ate.
01â 18:9 They said to him, "Where is your wife Sarah?" And he said, "There, in the tent."
01â 18:10 Then one said, "I will surely return to you in due season, and your wife Sarah shall have a son." And Sarah was listening at the tent entrance behind him.
01â 18:11 Now Abraham and Sarah were old, advanced in age; it had ceased to be with Sarah after the manner of women.
01â 18:12 So Sarah laughed to herself, saying, "After I have grown old, and my husband is old, shall I have pleasure?"
01â 18:13 The LORD said to Abraham, "Why did Sarah laugh, and say, 'Shall I indeed bear a child, now that I am old?'
01â 18:14 Is anything too wonderful for the LORD? At the set time I will return to you, in due season, and Sarah shall have a son."
01â 18:15 But Sarah denied, saying, "I did not laugh"; for she was afraid. He said, "Oh yes, you did laugh."
01â 18:16 Then the men set out from there, and they looked toward Sodom; and Abraham went with them to set them on their way.
01â 18:17 The LORD said, "Shall I hide from Abraham what I am about to do,
01â 18:18 seeing that Abraham shall become a great and mighty nation, and all the nations of the earth shall be blessed in him?
01â 18:19 No, for I have chosen him, that he may charge his children and his household after him to keep the way of the LORD by doing righteousness and justice; so that the LORD may bring about for Abraham what he has promised him."
01â 18:20 Then the LORD said, "How great is the outcry against Sodom and Gomorrah and how very grave their sin!
01â 18:21 I must go down and see whether they have done altogether according to the outcry that has come to me; and if not, I will know."
01â 18:22 So the men turned from there, and went toward Sodom, while Abraham remained standing before the LORD.
01â 18:23 Then Abraham came near and said, "Will you indeed sweep away the righteous with the wicked?
01â 18:24 Suppose there are fifty righteous within the city; will you then sweep away the place and not forgive it for the fifty righteous who are in it?
01â 18:25 Far be it from you to do such a thing, to slay the righteous with the wicked, so that the righteous fare as the wicked! Far be that from you! Shall not the Judge of all the earth do what is just?"
01â 18:26 And the LORD said, "If I find at Sodom fifty righteous in the city, I will forgive the whole place for their sake."
01â 18:27 Abraham answered, "Let me take it upon myself to speak to the Lord, I who am but dust and ashes.
01â 18:28 Suppose five of the fifty righteous are lacking? Will you destroy the whole city for lack of five?" And he said, "I will not destroy it if I find forty-five there."
01â 18:29 Again he spoke to him, "Suppose forty are found there." He answered, "For the sake of forty I will not do it."
01â 18:30 Then he said, "Oh do not let the Lord be angry if I speak. Suppose thirty are found there." He answered, "I will not do it, if I find thirty there."
01â 18:31 He said, "Let me take it upon myself to speak to the Lord. Suppose twenty are found there." He answered, "For the sake of twenty I will not destroy it."
01â 18:32 Then he said, "Oh do not let the Lord be angry if I speak just once more. Suppose ten are found there." He answered, "For the sake of ten I will not destroy it."
01â 18:33 And the LORD went his way, when he had finished speaking to Abraham; and Abraham returned to his place.
01â 19:1 The two angels came to Sodom in the evening, and Lot was sitting in the gateway of Sodom. When Lot saw them, he rose to meet them, and bowed down with his face to the ground.
01â 19:2 He said, "Please, my lords, turn aside to your servant's house and spend the night, and wash your feet; then you can rise early and go on your way." They said, "No; we will spend the night in the square."
01â 19:3 But he urged them strongly; so they turned aside to him and entered his house; and he made them a feast, and baked unleavened bread, and they ate.
01â 19:4 But before they lay down, the men of the city, the men of Sodom, both young and old, all the people to the last man, surrounded the house;
01â 19:5 and they called to Lot, "Where are the men who came to you tonight? Bring them out to us, so that we may know them."
01â 19:6 Lot went out of the door to the men, shut the door after him,
01â 19:7 and said, "I beg you, my brothers, do not act so wickedly.
01â 19:8 Look, I have two daughters who have not known a man; let me bring them out to you, and do to them as you please; only do nothing to these men, for they have come under the shelter of my roof."
01â 19:9 But they replied, "Stand back!" And they said, "This fellow came here as an alien, and he would play the judge! Now we will deal worse with you than with them." Then they pressed hard against the man Lot, and came near the door to break it down.
01â 19:10 But the men inside reached out their hands and brought Lot into the house with them, and shut the door.
01â 19:11 And they struck with blindness the men who were at the door of the house, both small and great, so that they were unable to find the door.
01â 19:12 Then the men said to Lot, "Have you anyone else here? Sons-in-law, sons, daughters, or anyone you have in the city--bring them out of the place.
01â 19:13 For we are about to destroy this place, because the outcry against its people has become great before the LORD, and the LORD has sent us to destroy it."
01â 19:14 So Lot went out and said to his sons-in-law, who were to marry his daughters, "Up, get out of this place; for the LORD is about to destroy the city." But he seemed to his sons-in-law to be jesting.
01â 19:15 When morning dawned, the angels urged Lot, saying, "Get up, take your wife and your two daughters who are here, or else you will be consumed in the punishment of the city."
01â 19:16 But he lingered; so the men seized him and his wife and his two daughters by the hand, the LORD being merciful to him, and they brought him out and left him outside the city.
01â 19:17 When they had brought them outside, they said, "Flee for your life; do not look back or stop anywhere in the Plain; flee to the hills, or else you will be consumed."
01â 19:18 And Lot said to them, "Oh, no, my lords;
01â 19:19 your servant has found favor with you, and you have shown me great kindness in saving my life; but I cannot flee to the hills, for fear the disaster will overtake me and I die.
01â 19:20 Look, that city is near enough to flee to, and it is a little one. Let me escape there--is it not a little one?--and my life will be saved!"
01â 19:21 He said to him, "Very well, I grant you this favor too, and will not overthrow the city of which you have spoken.
01â 19:22 Hurry, escape there, for I can do nothing until you arrive there." Therefore the city was called Zoar.
01â 19:23 The sun had risen on the earth when Lot came to Zoar.
01â 19:24 Then the LORD rained on Sodom and Gomorrah sulfur and fire from the LORD out of heaven;
01â 19:25 and he overthrew those cities, and all the Plain, and all the inhabitants of the cities, and what grew on the ground.
01â 19:26 But Lot's wife, behind him, looked back, and she became a pillar of salt.
01â 19:27 Abraham went early in the morning to the place where he had stood before the LORD;
01â 19:28 and he looked down toward Sodom and Gomorrah and toward all the land of the Plain and saw the smoke of the land going up like the smoke of a furnace.
01â 19:29 So it was that, when God destroyed the cities of the Plain, God remembered Abraham, and sent Lot out of the midst of the overthrow, when he overthrew the cities in which Lot had settled.
01â 19:30 Now Lot went up out of Zoar and settled in the hills with his two daughters, for he was afraid to stay in Zoar; so he lived in a cave with his two daughters.
01â 19:31 And the firstborn said to the younger, "Our father is old, and there is not a man on earth to come in to us after the manner of all the world.
01â 19:32 Come, let us make our father drink wine, and we will lie with him, so that we may preserve offspring through our father."
01â 19:33 So they made their father drink wine that night; and the firstborn went in, and lay with her father; he did not know when she lay down or when she rose.
01â 19:34 On the next day, the firstborn said to the younger, "Look, I lay last night with my father; let us make him drink wine tonight also; then you go in and lie with him, so that we may preserve offspring through our father."
01â 19:35 So they made their father drink wine that night also; and the younger rose, and lay with him; and he did not know when she lay down or when she rose.
01â 19:36 Thus both the daughters of Lot became pregnant by their father.
01â 19:37 The firstborn bore a son, and named him Moab; he is the ancestor of the Moabites to this day.
01â 19:38 The younger also bore a son and named him Ben-ammi; he is the ancestor of the Ammonites to this day.
01â 20:1 From there Abraham journeyed toward the region of the Negeb, and settled between Kadesh and Shur. While residing in Gerar as an alien,
01â 20:2 Abraham said of his wife Sarah, "She is my sister." And King Abimelech of Gerar sent and took Sarah.
01â 20:3 But God came to Abimelech in a dream by night, and said to him, "You are about to die because of the woman whom you have taken; for she is a married woman."
01â 20:4 Now Abimelech had not approached her; so he said, "Lord, will you destroy an innocent people?
01â 20:5 Did he not himself say to me, 'She is my sister'? And she herself said, 'He is my brother.' I did this in the integrity of my heart and the innocence of my hands."
01â 20:6 Then God said to him in the dream, "Yes, I know that you did this in the integrity of your heart; furthermore it was I who kept you from sinning against me. Therefore I did not let you touch her.
01â 20:7 Now then, return the man's wife; for he is a prophet, and he will pray for you and you shall live. But if you do not restore her, know that you shall surely die, you and all that are yours."
01â 20:8 So Abimelech rose early in the morning, and called all his servants and told them all these things; and the men were very much afraid.
01â 20:9 Then Abimelech called Abraham, and said to him, "What have you done to us? How have I sinned against you, that you have brought such great guilt on me and my kingdom? You have done things to me that ought not to be done."
01â 20:10 And Abimelech said to Abraham, "What were you thinking of, that you did this thing?"
01â 20:11 Abraham said, "I did it because I thought, There is no fear of God at all in this place, and they will kill me because of my wife.
01â 20:12 Besides, she is indeed my sister, the daughter of my father but not the daughter of my mother; and she became my wife.
01â 20:13 And when God caused me to wander from my father's house, I said to her, 'This is the kindness you must do me: at every place to which we come, say of me, He is my brother.'"
01â 20:14 Then Abimelech took sheep and oxen, and male and female slaves, and gave them to Abraham, and restored his wife Sarah to him.
01â 20:15 Abimelech said, "My land is before you; settle where it pleases you."
01â 20:16 To Sarah he said, "Look, I have given your brother a thousand pieces of silver; it is your exoneration before all who are with you; you are completely vindicated."
01â 20:17 Then Abraham prayed to God; and God healed Abimelech, and also healed his wife and female slaves so that they bore children.
01â 20:18 For the LORD had closed fast all the wombs of the house of Abimelech because of Sarah, Abraham's wife.
01â 21:1 The LORD dealt with Sarah as he had said, and the LORD did for Sarah as he had promised.
01â 21:2 Sarah conceived and bore Abraham a son in his old age, at the time of which God had spoken to him.
01â 21:3 Abraham gave the name Isaac to his son whom Sarah bore him.
01â 21:4 And Abraham circumcised his son Isaac when he was eight days old, as God had commanded him.
01â 21:5 Abraham was a hundred years old when his son Isaac was born to him.
01â 21:6 Now Sarah said, "God has brought laughter for me; everyone who hears will laugh with me."
01â 21:7 And she said, "Who would ever have said to Abraham that Sarah would nurse children? Yet I have borne him a son in his old age."
01â 21:8 The child grew, and was weaned; and Abraham made a great feast on the day that Isaac was weaned.
01â 21:9 But Sarah saw the son of Hagar the Egyptian, whom she had borne to Abraham, playing with her son Isaac.
01â 21:10 So she said to Abraham, "Cast out this slave woman with her son; for the son of this slave woman shall not inherit along with my son Isaac."
01â 21:11 The matter was very distressing to Abraham on account of his son.
01â 21:12 But God said to Abraham, "Do not be distressed because of the boy and because of your slave woman; whatever Sarah says to you, do as she tells you, for it is through Isaac that offspring shall be named for you.
01â 21:13 As for the son of the slave woman, I will make a nation of him also, because he is your offspring."
01â 21:14 So Abraham rose early in the morning, and took bread and a skin of water, and gave it to Hagar, putting it on her shoulder, along with the child, and sent her away. And she departed, and wandered about in the wilderness of Beer-sheba.
01â 21:15 When the water in the skin was gone, she cast the child under one of the bushes.
01â 21:16 Then she went and sat down opposite him a good way off, about the distance of a bowshot; for she said, "Do not let me look on the death of the child." And as she sat opposite him, she lifted up her voice and wept.
01â 21:17 And God heard the voice of the boy; and the angel of God called to Hagar from heaven, and said to her, "What troubles you, Hagar? Do not be afraid; for God has heard the voice of the boy where he is.
01â 21:18 Come, lift up the boy and hold him fast with your hand, for I will make a great nation of him."
01â 21:19 Then God opened her eyes and she saw a well of water. She went, and filled the skin with water, and gave the boy a drink.
01â 21:20 God was with the boy, and he grew up; he lived in the wilderness, and became an expert with the bow.
01â 21:21 He lived in the wilderness of Paran; and his mother got a wife for him from the land of Egypt.
01â 21:22 At that time Abimelech, with Phicol the commander of his army, said to Abraham, "God is with you in all that you do;
01â 21:23 now therefore swear to me here by God that you will not deal falsely with me or with my offspring or with my posterity, but as I have dealt loyally with you, you will deal with me and with the land where you have resided as an alien."
01â 21:24 And Abraham said, "I swear it."
01â 21:25 When Abraham complained to Abimelech about a well of water that Abimelech's servants had seized,
01â 21:26 Abimelech said, "I do not know who has done this; you did not tell me, and I have not heard of it until today."
01â 21:27 So Abraham took sheep and oxen and gave them to Abimelech, and the two men made a covenant.
01â 21:28 Abraham set apart seven ewe lambs of the flock.
01â 21:29 And Abimelech said to Abraham, "What is the meaning of these seven ewe lambs that you have set apart?"
01â 21:30 He said, "These seven ewe lambs you shall accept from my hand, in order that you may be a witness for me that I dug this well."
01â 21:31 Therefore that place was called Beer-sheba; because there both of them swore an oath.
01â 21:32 When they had made a covenant at Beer-sheba, Abimelech, with Phicol the commander of his army, left and returned to the land of the Philistines.
01â 21:33 Abraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beer-sheba, and called there on the name of the LORD, the Everlasting God.
01â 21:34 And Abraham resided as an alien many days in the land of the Philistines.
01â 22:1 After these things God tested Abraham. He said to him, "Abraham!" And he said, "Here I am."
01â 22:2 He said, "Take your son, your only son Isaac, whom you love, and go to the land of Moriah, and offer him there as a burnt offering on one of the mountains that I shall show you."
01â 22:3 So Abraham rose early in the morning, saddled his donkey, and took two of his young men with him, and his son Isaac; he cut the wood for the burnt offering, and set out and went to the place in the distance that God had shown him.
01â 22:4 On the third day Abraham looked up and saw the place far away.
01â 22:5 Then Abraham said to his young men, "Stay here with the donkey; the boy and I will go over there; we will worship, and then we will come back to you."
01â 22:6 Abraham took the wood of the burnt offering and laid it on his son Isaac, and he himself carried the fire and the knife. So the two of them walked on together.
01â 22:7 Isaac said to his father Abraham, "Father!" And he said, "Here I am, my son." He said, "The fire and the wood are here, but where is the lamb for a burnt offering?"
01â 22:8 Abraham said, "God himself will provide the lamb for a burnt offering, my son." So the two of them walked on together.
01â 22:9 When they came to the place that God had shown him, Abraham built an altar there and laid the wood in order. He bound his son Isaac, and laid him on the altar, on top of the wood.
01â 22:10 Then Abraham reached out his hand and took the knife to kill his son.
01â 22:11 But the angel of the LORD called to him from heaven, and said, "Abraham, Abraham!" And he said, "Here I am."
01â 22:12 He said, "Do not lay your hand on the boy or do anything to him; for now I know that you fear God, since you have not withheld your son, your only son, from me."
01â 22:13 And Abraham looked up and saw a ram, caught in a thicket by its horns. Abraham went and took the ram and offered it up as a burnt offering instead of his son.
01â 22:14 So Abraham called that place "The LORD will provide"; as it is said to this day, "On the mount of the LORD it shall be provided."
01â 22:15 The angel of the LORD called to Abraham a second time from heaven,
01â 22:16 and said, "By myself I have sworn, says the LORD: Because you have done this, and have not withheld your son, your only son,
01â 22:17 I will indeed bless you, and I will make your offspring as numerous as the stars of heaven and as the sand that is on the seashore. And your offspring shall possess the gate of their enemies,
01â 22:18 and by your offspring shall all the nations of the earth gain blessing for themselves, because you have obeyed my voice."
01â 22:19 So Abraham returned to his young men, and they arose and went together to Beer-sheba; and Abraham lived at Beer-sheba.
01â 22:20 Now after these things it was told Abraham, "Milcah also has borne children, to your brother Nahor:
01â 22:21 Uz the firstborn, Buz his brother, Kemuel the father of Aram,
01â 22:22 Chesed, Hazo, Pildash, Jidlaph, and Bethuel."
01â 22:23 Bethuel became the father of Rebekah. These eight Milcah bore to Nahor, Abraham's brother.
01â 22:24 Moreover, his concubine, whose name was Reumah, bore Tebah, Gaham, Tahash, and Maacah.
01â 23:1 Sarah lived one hundred twenty-seven years; this was the length of Sarah's life.
01â 23:2 And Sarah died at Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan; and Abraham went in to mourn for Sarah and to weep for her.
01â 23:3 Abraham rose up from beside his dead, and said to the Hittites,
01â 23:4 "I am a stranger and an alien residing among you; give me property among you for a burying place, so that I may bury my dead out of my sight."
01â 23:5 The Hittites answered Abraham,
01â 23:6 "Hear us, my lord; you are a mighty prince among us. Bury your dead in the choicest of our burial places; none of us will withhold from you any burial ground for burying your dead."
01â 23:7 Abraham rose and bowed to the Hittites, the people of the land.
01â 23:8 He said to them, "If you are willing that I should bury my dead out of my sight, hear me, and entreat for me Ephron son of Zohar,
01â 23:9 so that he may give me the cave of Machpelah, which he owns; it is at the end of his field. For the full price let him give it to me in your presence as a possession for a burying place."
01â 23:10 Now Ephron was sitting among the Hittites; and Ephron the Hittite answered Abraham in the hearing of the Hittites, of all who went in at the gate of his city,
01â 23:11 "No, my lord, hear me; I give you the field, and I give you the cave that is in it; in the presence of my people I give it to you; bury your dead."
01â 23:12 Then Abraham bowed down before the people of the land.
01â 23:13 He said to Ephron in the hearing of the people of the land, "If you only will listen to me! I will give the price of the field; accept it from me, so that I may bury my dead there."
01â 23:14 Ephron answered Abraham,
01â 23:15 "My lord, listen to me; a piece of land worth four hundred shekels of silver--what is that between you and me? Bury your dead."
01â 23:16 Abraham agreed with Ephron; and Abraham weighed out for Ephron the silver that he had named in the hearing of the Hittites, four hundred shekels of silver, according to the weights current among the merchants.
01â 23:17 So the field of Ephron in Machpelah, which was to the east of Mamre, the field with the cave that was in it and all the trees that were in the field, throughout its whole area, passed
01â 23:18 to Abraham as a possession in the presence of the Hittites, in the presence of all who went in at the gate of his city.
01â 23:19 After this, Abraham buried Sarah his wife in the cave of the field of Machpelah facing Mamre (that is, Hebron) in the land of Canaan.
01â 23:20 The field and the cave that is in it passed from the Hittites into Abraham's possession as a burying place.
01â 24:1 Now Abraham was old, well advanced in years; and the LORD had blessed Abraham in all things.
01â 24:2 Abraham said to his servant, the oldest of his house, who had charge of all that he had, "Put your hand under my thigh
01â 24:3 and I will make you swear by the LORD, the God of heaven and earth, that you will not get a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites, among whom I live,
01â 24:4 but will go to my country and to my kindred and get a wife for my son Isaac."
01â 24:5 The servant said to him, "Perhaps the woman may not be willing to follow me to this land; must I then take your son back to the land from which you came?"
01â 24:6 Abraham said to him, "See to it that you do not take my son back there.
01â 24:7 The LORD, the God of heaven, who took me from my father's house and from the land of my birth, and who spoke to me and swore to me, 'To your offspring I will give this land,' he will send his angel before you, and you shall take a wife for my son from there.
01â 24:8 But if the woman is not willing to follow you, then you will be free from this oath of mine; only you must not take my son back there."
01â 24:9 So the servant put his hand under the thigh of Abraham his master and swore to him concerning this matter.
01â 24:10 Then the servant took ten of his master's camels and departed, taking all kinds of choice gifts from his master; and he set out and went to Aram-naharaim, to the city of Nahor.
01â 24:11 He made the camels kneel down outside the city by the well of water; it was toward evening, the time when women go out to draw water.
01â 24:12 And he said, "O LORD, God of my master Abraham, please grant me success today and show steadfast love to my master Abraham.
01â 24:13 I am standing here by the spring of water, and the daughters of the townspeople are coming out to draw water.
01â 24:14 Let the girl to whom I shall say, 'Please offer your jar that I may drink,' and who shall say, 'Drink, and I will water your camels'--let her be the one whom you have appointed for your servant Isaac. By this I shall know that you have shown steadfast love to my master."
01â 24:15 Before he had finished speaking, there was Rebekah, who was born to Bethuel son of Milcah, the wife of Nahor, Abraham's brother, coming out with her water jar on her shoulder.
01â 24:16 The girl was very fair to look upon, a virgin, whom no man had known. She went down to the spring, filled her jar, and came up.
01â 24:17 Then the servant ran to meet her and said, "Please let me sip a little water from your jar."
01â 24:18 "Drink, my lord," she said, and quickly lowered her jar upon her hand and gave him a drink.
01â 24:19 When she had finished giving him a drink, she said, "I will draw for your camels also, until they have finished drinking."
01â 24:20 So she quickly emptied her jar into the trough and ran again to the well to draw, and she drew for all his camels.
01â 24:21 The man gazed at her in silence to learn whether or not the LORD had made his journey successful.
01â 24:22 When the camels had finished drinking, the man took a gold nose-ring weighing a half shekel, and two bracelets for her arms weighing ten gold shekels,
01â 24:23 and said, "Tell me whose daughter you are. Is there room in your father's house for us to spend the night?"
01â 24:24 She said to him, "I am the daughter of Bethuel son of Milcah, whom she bore to Nahor."
01â 24:25 She added, "We have plenty of straw and fodder and a place to spend the night."
01â 24:26 The man bowed his head and worshiped the LORD
01â 24:27 and said, "Blessed be the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who has not forsaken his steadfast love and his faithfulness toward my master. As for me, the LORD has led me on the way to the house of my master's kin."
01â 24:28 Then the girl ran and told her mother's household about these things.
01â 24:29 Rebekah had a brother whose name was Laban; and Laban ran out to the man, to the spring.
01â 24:30 As soon as he had seen the nose-ring, and the bracelets on his sister's arms, and when he heard the words of his sister Rebekah, "Thus the man spoke to me," he went to the man; and there he was, standing by the camels at the spring.
01â 24:31 He said, "Come in, O blessed of the LORD. Why do you stand outside when I have prepared the house and a place for the camels?"
01â 24:32 So the man came into the house; and Laban unloaded the camels, and gave him straw and fodder for the camels, and water to wash his feet and the feet of the men who were with him.
01â 24:33 Then food was set before him to eat; but he said, "I will not eat until I have told my errand." He said, "Speak on."
01â 24:34 So he said, "I am Abraham's servant.
01â 24:35 The LORD has greatly blessed my master, and he has become wealthy; he has given him flocks and herds, silver and gold, male and female slaves, camels and donkeys.
01â 24:36 And Sarah my master's wife bore a son to my master when she was old; and he has given him all that he has.
01â 24:37 My master made me swear, saying, 'You shall not take a wife for my son from the daughters of the Canaanites, in whose land I live;
01â 24:38 but you shall go to my father's house, to my kindred, and get a wife for my son.'
01â 24:39 I said to my master, 'Perhaps the woman will not follow me.'
01â 24:40 But he said to me, 'The LORD, before whom I walk, will send his angel with you and make your way successful. You shall get a wife for my son from my kindred, from my father's house.
01â 24:41 Then you will be free from my oath, when you come to my kindred; even if they will not give her to you, you will be free from my oath.'
01â 24:42 "I came today to the spring, and said, 'O LORD, the God of my master Abraham, if now you will only make successful the way I am going!
01â 24:43 I am standing here by the spring of water; let the young woman who comes out to draw, to whom I shall say, "Please give me a little water from your jar to drink,"
01â 24:44 and who will say to me, "Drink, and I will draw for your camels also"--let her be the woman whom the LORD has appointed for my master's son.'
01â 24:45 "Before I had finished speaking in my heart, there was Rebekah coming out with her water jar on her shoulder; and she went down to the spring, and drew. I said to her, 'Please let me drink.'
01â 24:46 She quickly let down her jar from her shoulder, and said, 'Drink, and I will also water your camels.' So I drank, and she also watered the camels.
01â 24:47 Then I asked her, 'Whose daughter are you?' She said, 'The daughter of Bethuel, Nahor's son, whom Milcah bore to him.' So I put the ring on her nose, and the bracelets on her arms.
01â 24:48 Then I bowed my head and worshiped the LORD, and blessed the LORD, the God of my master Abraham, who had led me by the right way to obtain the daughter of my master's kinsman for his son.
01â 24:49 Now then, if you will deal loyally and truly with my master, tell me; and if not, tell me, so that I may turn either to the right hand or to the left."
01â 24:50 Then Laban and Bethuel answered, "The thing comes from the LORD; we cannot speak to you anything bad or good.
01â 24:51 Look, Rebekah is before you, take her and go, and let her be the wife of your master's son, as the LORD has spoken."
01â 24:52 When Abraham's servant heard their words, he bowed himself to the ground before the LORD.
01â 24:53 And the servant brought out jewelry of silver and of gold, and garments, and gave them to Rebekah; he also gave to her brother and to her mother costly ornaments.
01â 24:54 Then he and the men who were with him ate and drank, and they spent the night there. When they rose in the morning, he said, "Send me back to my master."
01â 24:55 Her brother and her mother said, "Let the girl remain with us a while, at least ten days; after that she may go."
01â 24:56 But he said to them, "Do not delay me, since the LORD has made my journey successful; let me go that I may go to my master."
01â 24:57 They said, "We will call the girl, and ask her."
01â 24:58 And they called Rebekah, and said to her, "Will you go with this man?" She said, "I will."
01â 24:59 So they sent away their sister Rebekah and her nurse along with Abraham's servant and his men.
01â 24:60 And they blessed Rebekah and said to her, "May you, our sister, become thousands of myriads; may your offspring gain possession of the gates of their foes."
01â 24:61 Then Rebekah and her maids rose up, mounted the camels, and followed the man; thus the servant took Rebekah, and went his way.
01â 24:62 Now Isaac had come from Beer-lahai-roi, and was settled in the Negeb.
01â 24:63 Isaac went out in the evening to walk in the field; and looking up, he saw camels coming.
01â 24:64 And Rebekah looked up, and when she saw Isaac, she slipped quickly from the camel,
01â 24:65 and said to the servant, "Who is the man over there, walking in the field to meet us?" The servant said, "It is my master." So she took her veil and covered herself.
01â 24:66 And the servant told Isaac all the things that he had done.
01â 24:67 Then Isaac brought her into his mother Sarah's tent. He took Rebekah, and she became his wife; and he loved her. So Isaac was comforted after his mother's death.
01â 25:1 Abraham took another wife, whose name was Keturah.
01â 25:2 She bore him Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah.
01â 25:3 Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan. The sons of Dedan were Asshurim, Letushim, and Leummim.
01â 25:4 The sons of Midian were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah. All these were the children of Keturah.
01â 25:5 Abraham gave all he had to Isaac.
01â 25:6 But to the sons of his concubines Abraham gave gifts, while he was still living, and he sent them away from his son Isaac, eastward to the east country.
01â 25:7 This is the length of Abraham's life, one hundred seventy-five years.
01â 25:8 Abraham breathed his last and died in a good old age, an old man and full of years, and was gathered to his people.
01â 25:9 His sons Isaac and Ishmael buried him in the cave of Machpelah, in the field of Ephron son of Zohar the Hittite, east of Mamre,
01â 25:10 the field that Abraham purchased from the Hittites. There Abraham was buried, with his wife Sarah.
01â 25:11 After the death of Abraham God blessed his son Isaac. And Isaac settled at Beer-lahai-roi.
01â 25:12 These are the descendants of Ishmael, Abraham's son, whom Hagar the Egyptian, Sarah's slave-girl, bore to Abraham.
01â 25:13 These are the names of the sons of Ishmael, named in the order of their birth: Nebaioth, the firstborn of Ishmael; and Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,
01â 25:14 Mishma, Dumah, Massa,
01â 25:15 Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah.
01â 25:16 These are the sons of Ishmael and these are their names, by their villages and by their encampments, twelve princes according to their tribes.
01â 25:17 (This is the length of the life of Ishmael, one hundred thirty-seven years; he breathed his last and died, and was gathered to his people.)
01â 25:18 They settled from Havilah to Shur, which is opposite Egypt in the direction of Assyria; he settled down alongside of all his people.
01â 25:19 These are the descendants of Isaac, Abraham's son: Abraham was the father of Isaac,
01â 25:20 and Isaac was forty years old when he married Rebekah, daughter of Bethuel the Aramean of Paddan-aram, sister of Laban the Aramean.
01â 25:21 Isaac prayed to the LORD for his wife, because she was barren; and the LORD granted his prayer, and his wife Rebekah conceived.
01â 25:22 The children struggled together within her; and she said, "If it is to be this way, why do I live?" So she went to inquire of the LORD.
01â 25:23 And the LORD said to her, "Two nations are in your womb, and two peoples born of you shall be divided; the one shall be stronger than the other, the elder shall serve the younger."
01â 25:24 When her time to give birth was at hand, there were twins in her womb.
01â 25:25 The first came out red, all his body like a hairy mantle; so they named him Esau.
01â 25:26 Afterward his brother came out, with his hand gripping Esau's heel; so he was named Jacob. Isaac was sixty years old when she bore them.
01â 25:27 When the boys grew up, Esau was a skillful hunter, a man of the field, while Jacob was a quiet man, living in tents.
01â 25:28 Isaac loved Esau, because he was fond of game; but Rebekah loved Jacob.
01â 25:29 Once when Jacob was cooking a stew, Esau came in from the field, and he was famished.
01â 25:30 Esau said to Jacob, "Let me eat some of that red stuff, for I am famished!" (Therefore he was called Edom.)
01â 25:31 Jacob said, "First sell me your birthright."
01â 25:32 Esau said, "I am about to die; of what use is a birthright to me?"
01â 25:33 Jacob said, "Swear to me first." So he swore to him, and sold his birthright to Jacob.
01â 25:34 Then Jacob gave Esau bread and lentil stew, and he ate and drank, and rose and went his way. Thus Esau despised his birthright.
01â 26:1 Now there was a famine in the land, besides the former famine that had occurred in the days of Abraham. And Isaac went to Gerar, to King Abimelech of the Philistines.
01â 26:2 The LORD appeared to Isaac and said, "Do not go down to Egypt; settle in the land that I shall show you.
01â 26:3 Reside in this land as an alien, and I will be with you, and will bless you; for to you and to your descendants I will give all these lands, and I will fulfill the oath that I swore to your father Abraham.
01â 26:4 I will make your offspring as numerous as the stars of heaven, and will give to your offspring all these lands; and all the nations of the earth shall gain blessing for themselves through your offspring,
01â 26:5 because Abraham obeyed my voice and kept my charge, my commandments, my statutes, and my laws."
01â 26:6 So Isaac settled in Gerar.
01â 26:7 When the men of the place asked him about his wife, he said, "She is my sister"; for he was afraid to say, "My wife," thinking, "or else the men of the place might kill me for the sake of Rebekah, because she is attractive in appearance."
01â 26:8 When Isaac had been there a long time, King Abimelech of the Philistines looked out of a window and saw him fondling his wife Rebekah.
01â 26:9 So Abimelech called for Isaac, and said, "So she is your wife! Why then did you say, 'She is my sister'?" Isaac said to him, "Because I thought I might die because of her."
01â 26:10 Abimelech said, "What is this you have done to us? One of the people might easily have lain with your wife, and you would have brought guilt upon us."
01â 26:11 So Abimelech warned all the people, saying, "Whoever touches this man or his wife shall be put to death."
01â 26:12 Isaac sowed seed in that land, and in the same year reaped a hundredfold. The LORD blessed him,
01â 26:13 and the man became rich; he prospered more and more until he became very wealthy.
01â 26:14 He had possessions of flocks and herds, and a great household, so that the Philistines envied him.
01â 26:15 (Now the Philistines had stopped up and filled with earth all the wells that his father's servants had dug in the days of his father Abraham.)
01â 26:16 And Abimelech said to Isaac, "Go away from us; you have become too powerful for us."
01â 26:17 So Isaac departed from there and camped in the valley of Gerar and settled there.
01â 26:18 Isaac dug again the wells of water that had been dug in the days of his father Abraham; for the Philistines had stopped them up after the death of Abraham; and he gave them the names that his father had given them.
01â 26:19 But when Isaac's servants dug in the valley and found there a well of spring water,
01â 26:20 the herders of Gerar quarreled with Isaac's herders, saying, "The water is ours." So he called the well Esek, because they contended with him.
01â 26:21 Then they dug another well, and they quarreled over that one also; so he called it Sitnah.
01â 26:22 He moved from there and dug another well, and they did not quarrel over it; so he called it Rehoboth, saying, "Now the LORD has made room for us, and we shall be fruitful in the land."
01â 26:23 From there he went up to Beer-sheba.
01â 26:24 And that very night the LORD appeared to him and said, "I am the God of your father Abraham; do not be afraid, for I am with you and will bless you and make your offspring numerous for my servant Abraham's sake."
01â 26:25 So he built an altar there, called on the name of the LORD, and pitched his tent there. And there Isaac's servants dug a well.
01â 26:26 Then Abimelech went to him from Gerar, with Ahuzzath his adviser and Phicol the commander of his army.
01â 26:27 Isaac said to them, "Why have you come to me, seeing that you hate me and have sent me away from you?"
01â 26:28 They said, "We see plainly that the LORD has been with you; so we say, let there be an oath between you and us, and let us make a covenant with you
01â 26:29 so that you will do us no harm, just as we have not touched you and have done to you nothing but good and have sent you away in peace. You are now the blessed of the LORD."
01â 26:30 So he made them a feast, and they ate and drank.
01â 26:31 In the morning they rose early and exchanged oaths; and Isaac set them on their way, and they departed from him in peace.
01â 26:32 That same day Isaac's servants came and told him about the well that they had dug, and said to him, "We have found water!"
01â 26:33 He called it Shibah; therefore the name of the city is Beer-sheba to this day.
01â 26:34 When Esau was forty years old, he married Judith daughter of Beeri the Hittite, and Basemath daughter of Elon the Hittite;
01â 26:35 and they made life bitter for Isaac and Rebekah.
01â 27:1 When Isaac was old and his eyes were dim so that he could not see, he called his elder son Esau and said to him, "My son"; and he answered, "Here I am."
01â 27:2 He said, "See, I am old; I do not know the day of my death.
01â 27:3 Now then, take your weapons, your quiver and your bow, and go out to the field, and hunt game for me.
01â 27:4 Then prepare for me savory food, such as I like, and bring it to me to eat, so that I may bless you before I die."
01â 27:5 Now Rebekah was listening when Isaac spoke to his son Esau. So when Esau went to the field to hunt for game and bring it,
01â 27:6 Rebekah said to her son Jacob, "I heard your father say to your brother Esau,
01â 27:7 'Bring me game, and prepare for me savory food to eat, that I may bless you before the LORD before I die.'
01â 27:8 Now therefore, my son, obey my word as I command you.
01â 27:9 Go to the flock, and get me two choice kids, so that I may prepare from them savory food for your father, such as he likes;
01â 27:10 and you shall take it to your father to eat, so that he may bless you before he dies."
01â 27:11 But Jacob said to his mother Rebekah, "Look, my brother Esau is a hairy man, and I am a man of smooth skin.
01â 27:12 Perhaps my father will feel me, and I shall seem to be mocking him, and bring a curse on myself and not a blessing."
01â 27:13 His mother said to him, "Let your curse be on me, my son; only obey my word, and go, get them for me."
01â 27:14 So he went and got them and brought them to his mother; and his mother prepared savory food, such as his father loved.
01â 27:15 Then Rebekah took the best garments of her elder son Esau, which were with her in the house, and put them on her younger son Jacob;
01â 27:16 and she put the skins of the kids on his hands and on the smooth part of his neck.
01â 27:17 Then she handed the savory food, and the bread that she had prepared, to her son Jacob.
01â 27:18 So he went in to his father, and said, "My father"; and he said, "Here I am; who are you, my son?"
01â 27:19 Jacob said to his father, "I am Esau your firstborn. I have done as you told me; now sit up and eat of my game, so that you may bless me."
01â 27:20 But Isaac said to his son, "How is it that you have found it so quickly, my son?" He answered, "Because the LORD your God granted me success."
01â 27:21 Then Isaac said to Jacob, "Come near, that I may feel you, my son, to know whether you are really my son Esau or not."
01â 27:22 So Jacob went up to his father Isaac, who felt him and said, "The voice is Jacob's voice, but the hands are the hands of Esau."
01â 27:23 He did not recognize him, because his hands were hairy like his brother Esau's hands; so he blessed him.
01â 27:24 He said, "Are you really my son Esau?" He answered, "I am."
01â 27:25 Then he said, "Bring it to me, that I may eat of my son's game and bless you." So he brought it to him, and he ate; and he brought him wine, and he drank.
01â 27:26 Then his father Isaac said to him, "Come near and kiss me, my son."
01â 27:27 So he came near and kissed him; and he smelled the smell of his garments, and blessed him, and said, "Ah, the smell of my son is like the smell of a field that the LORD has blessed.
01â 27:28 May God give you of the dew of heaven, and of the fatness of the earth, and plenty of grain and wine.
01â 27:29 Let peoples serve you, and nations bow down to you. Be lord over your brothers, and may your mother's sons bow down to you. Cursed be everyone who curses you, and blessed be everyone who blesses you!"
01â 27:30 As soon as Isaac had finished blessing Jacob, when Jacob had scarcely gone out from the presence of his father Isaac, his brother Esau came in from his hunting.
01â 27:31 He also prepared savory food, and brought it to his father. And he said to his father, "Let my father sit up and eat of his son's game, so that you may bless me."
01â 27:32 His father Isaac said to him, "Who are you?" He answered, "I am your firstborn son, Esau."
01â 27:33 Then Isaac trembled violently, and said, "Who was it then that hunted game and brought it to me, and I ate it all before you came, and I have blessed him?--yes, and blessed he shall be!"
01â 27:34 When Esau heard his father's words, he cried out with an exceedingly great and bitter cry, and said to his father, "Bless me, me also, father!"
01â 27:35 But he said, "Your brother came deceitfully, and he has taken away your blessing."
01â 27:36 Esau said, "Is he not rightly named Jacob? For he has supplanted me these two times. He took away my birthright; and look, now he has taken away my blessing." Then he said, "Have you not reserved a blessing for me?"
01â 27:37 Isaac answered Esau, "I have already made him your lord, and I have given him all his brothers as servants, and with grain and wine I have sustained him. What then can I do for you, my son?"
01â 27:38 Esau said to his father, "Have you only one blessing, father? Bless me, me also, father!" And Esau lifted up his voice and wept.
01â 27:39 Then his father Isaac answered him: "See, away from the fatness of the earth shall your home be, and away from the dew of heaven on high.
01â 27:40 By your sword you shall live, and you shall serve your brother; but when you break loose, you shall break his yoke from your neck."
01â 27:41 Now Esau hated Jacob because of the blessing with which his father had blessed him, and Esau said to himself, "The days of mourning for my father are approaching; then I will kill my brother Jacob."
01â 27:42 But the words of her elder son Esau were told to Rebekah; so she sent and called her younger son Jacob and said to him, "Your brother Esau is consoling himself by planning to kill you.
01â 27:43 Now therefore, my son, obey my voice; flee at once to my brother Laban in Haran,
01â 27:44 and stay with him a while, until your brother's fury turns away--
01â 27:45 until your brother's anger against you turns away, and he forgets what you have done to him; then I will send, and bring you back from there. Why should I lose both of you in one day?"
01â 27:46 Then Rebekah said to Isaac, "I am weary of my life because of the Hittite women. If Jacob marries one of the Hittite women such as these, one of the women of the land, what good will my life be to me?"
01â 28:1 Then Isaac called Jacob and blessed him, and charged him, "You shall not marry one of the Canaanite women.
01â 28:2 Go at once to Paddan-aram to the house of Bethuel, your mother's father; and take as wife from there one of the daughters of Laban, your mother's brother.
01â 28:3 May God Almighty bless you and make you fruitful and numerous, that you may become a company of peoples.
01â 28:4 May he give to you the blessing of Abraham, to you and to your offspring with you, so that you may take possession of the land where you now live as an alien--land that God gave to Abraham."
01â 28:5 Thus Isaac sent Jacob away; and he went to Paddan-aram, to Laban son of Bethuel the Aramean, the brother of Rebekah, Jacob's and Esau's mother.
01â 28:6 Now Esau saw that Isaac had blessed Jacob and sent him away to Paddan-aram to take a wife from there, and that as he blessed him he charged him, "You shall not marry one of the Canaanite women,"
01â 28:7 and that Jacob had obeyed his father and his mother and gone to Paddan-aram.
01â 28:8 So when Esau saw that the Canaanite women did not please his father Isaac,
01â 28:9 Esau went to Ishmael and took Mahalath daughter of Abraham's son Ishmael, and sister of Nebaioth, to be his wife in addition to the wives he had.
01â 28:10 Jacob left Beer-sheba and went toward Haran.
01â 28:11 He came to a certain place and stayed there for the night, because the sun had set. Taking one of the stones of the place, he put it under his head and lay down in that place.
01â 28:12 And he dreamed that there was a ladder set up on the earth, the top of it reaching to heaven; and the angels of God were ascending and descending on it.
01â 28:13 And the LORD stood beside him and said, "I am the LORD, the God of Abraham your father and the God of Isaac; the land on which you lie I will give to you and to your offspring;
01â 28:14 and your offspring shall be like the dust of the earth, and you shall spread abroad to the west and to the east and to the north and to the south; and all the families of the earth shall be blessed in you and in your offspring.
01â 28:15 Know that I am with you and will keep you wherever you go, and will bring you back to this land; for I will not leave you until I have done what I have promised you."
01â 28:16 Then Jacob woke from his sleep and said, "Surely the LORD is in this place--and I did not know it!"
01â 28:17 And he was afraid, and said, "How awesome is this place! This is none other than the house of God, and this is the gate of heaven."
01â 28:18 So Jacob rose early in the morning, and he took the stone that he had put under his head and set it up for a pillar and poured oil on the top of it.
01â 28:19 He called that place Bethel; but the name of the city was Luz at the first.
01â 28:20 Then Jacob made a vow, saying, "If God will be with me, and will keep me in this way that I go, and will give me bread to eat and clothing to wear,
01â 28:21 so that I come again to my father's house in peace, then the LORD shall be my God,
01â 28:22 and this stone, which I have set up for a pillar, shall be God's house; and of all that you give me I will surely give one tenth to you."
01â 29:1 Then Jacob went on his journey, and came to the land of the people of the east.
01â 29:2 As he looked, he saw a well in the field and three flocks of sheep lying there beside it; for out of that well the flocks were watered. The stone on the well's mouth was large,
01â 29:3 and when all the flocks were gathered there, the shepherds would roll the stone from the mouth of the well, and water the sheep, and put the stone back in its place on the mouth of the well.
01â 29:4 Jacob said to them, "My brothers, where do you come from?" They said, "We are from Haran."
01â 29:5 He said to them, "Do you know Laban son of Nahor?" They said, "We do."
01â 29:6 He said to them, "Is it well with him?" "Yes," they replied, "and here is his daughter Rachel, coming with the sheep."
01â 29:7 He said, "Look, it is still broad daylight; it is not time for the animals to be gathered together. Water the sheep, and go, pasture them."
01â 29:8 But they said, "We cannot until all the flocks are gathered together, and the stone is rolled from the mouth of the well; then we water the sheep."
01â 29:9 While he was still speaking with them, Rachel came with her father's sheep; for she kept them.
01â 29:10 Now when Jacob saw Rachel, the daughter of his mother's brother Laban, and the sheep of his mother's brother Laban, Jacob went up and rolled the stone from the well's mouth, and watered the flock of his mother's brother Laban.
01â 29:11 Then Jacob kissed Rachel, and wept aloud.
01â 29:12 And Jacob told Rachel that he was her father's kinsman, and that he was Rebekah's son; and she ran and told her father.
01â 29:13 When Laban heard the news about his sister's son Jacob, he ran to meet him; he embraced him and kissed him, and brought him to his house. Jacob told Laban all these things,
01â 29:14 and Laban said to him, "Surely you are my bone and my flesh!" And he stayed with him a month.
01â 29:15 Then Laban said to Jacob, "Because you are my kinsman, should you therefore serve me for nothing? Tell me, what shall your wages be?"
01â 29:16 Now Laban had two daughters; the name of the elder was Leah, and the name of the younger was Rachel.
01â 29:17 Leah's eyes were lovely, and Rachel was graceful and beautiful.
01â 29:18 Jacob loved Rachel; so he said, "I will serve you seven years for your younger daughter Rachel."
01â 29:19 Laban said, "It is better that I give her to you than that I should give her to any other man; stay with me."
01â 29:20 So Jacob served seven years for Rachel, and they seemed to him but a few days because of the love he had for her.
01â 29:21 Then Jacob said to Laban, "Give me my wife that I may go in to her, for my time is completed."
01â 29:22 So Laban gathered together all the people of the place, and made a feast.
01â 29:23 But in the evening he took his daughter Leah and brought her to Jacob; and he went in to her.
01â 29:24 (Laban gave his maid Zilpah to his daughter Leah to be her maid.)
01â 29:25 When morning came, it was Leah! And Jacob said to Laban, "What is this you have done to me? Did I not serve with you for Rachel? Why then have you deceived me?"
01â 29:26 Laban said, "This is not done in our country--giving the younger before the firstborn.
01â 29:27 Complete the week of this one, and we will give you the other also in return for serving me another seven years."
01â 29:28 Jacob did so, and completed her week; then Laban gave him his daughter Rachel as a wife.
01â 29:29 (Laban gave his maid Bilhah to his daughter Rachel to be her maid.)
01â 29:30 So Jacob went in to Rachel also, and he loved Rachel more than Leah. He served Laban for another seven years.
01â 29:31 When the LORD saw that Leah was unloved, he opened her womb; but Rachel was barren.
01â 29:32 Leah conceived and bore a son, and she named him Reuben; for she said, "Because the LORD has looked on my affliction; surely now my husband will love me."
01â 29:33 She conceived again and bore a son, and said, "Because the LORD has heard that I am hated, he has given me this son also"; and she named him Simeon.
01â 29:34 Again she conceived and bore a son, and said, "Now this time my husband will be joined to me, because I have borne him three sons"; therefore he was named Levi.
01â 29:35 She conceived again and bore a son, and said, "This time I will praise the LORD"; therefore she named him Judah; then she ceased bearing.
01â 30:1 When Rachel saw that she bore Jacob no children, she envied her sister; and she said to Jacob, "Give me children, or I shall die!"
01â 30:2 Jacob became very angry with Rachel and said, "Am I in the place of God, who has withheld from you the fruit of the womb?"
01â 30:3 Then she said, "Here is my maid Bilhah; go in to her, that she may bear upon my knees and that I too may have children through her."
01â 30:4 So she gave him her maid Bilhah as a wife; and Jacob went in to her.
01â 30:5 And Bilhah conceived and bore Jacob a son.
01â 30:6 Then Rachel said, "God has judged me, and has also heard my voice and given me a son"; therefore she named him Dan.
01â 30:7 Rachel's maid Bilhah conceived again and bore Jacob a second son.
01â 30:8 Then Rachel said, "With mighty wrestlings I have wrestled with my sister, and have prevailed"; so she named him Naphtali.
01â 30:9 When Leah saw that she had ceased bearing children, she took her maid Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as a wife.
01â 30:10 Then Leah's maid Zilpah bore Jacob a son.
01â 30:11 And Leah said, "Good fortune!" so she named him Gad.
01â 30:12 Leah's maid Zilpah bore Jacob a second son.
01â 30:13 And Leah said, "Happy am I! For the women will call me happy"; so she named him Asher.
01â 30:14 In the days of wheat harvest Reuben went and found mandrakes in the field, and brought them to his mother Leah. Then Rachel said to Leah, "Please give me some of your son's mandrakes."
01â 30:15 But she said to her, "Is it a small matter that you have taken away my husband? Would you take away my son's mandrakes also?" Rachel said, "Then he may lie with you tonight for your son's mandrakes."
01â 30:16 When Jacob came from the field in the evening, Leah went out to meet him, and said, "You must come in to me; for I have hired you with my son's mandrakes." So he lay with her that night.
01â 30:17 And God heeded Leah, and she conceived and bore Jacob a fifth son.
01â 30:18 Leah said, "God has given me my hire because I gave my maid to my husband"; so she named him Issachar.
01â 30:19 And Leah conceived again, and she bore Jacob a sixth son.
01â 30:20 Then Leah said, "God has endowed me with a good dowry; now my husband will honor me, because I have borne him six sons"; so she named him Zebulun.
01â 30:21 Afterwards she bore a daughter, and named her Dinah.
01â 30:22 Then God remembered Rachel, and God heeded her and opened her womb.
01â 30:23 She conceived and bore a son, and said, "God has taken away my reproach";
01â 30:24 and she named him Joseph, saying, "May the LORD add to me another son!"
01â 30:25 When Rachel had borne Joseph, Jacob said to Laban, "Send me away, that I may go to my own home and country.
01â 30:26 Give me my wives and my children for whom I have served you, and let me go; for you know very well the service I have given you."
01â 30:27 But Laban said to him, "If you will allow me to say so, I have learned by divination that the LORD has blessed me because of you;
01â 30:28 name your wages, and I will give it."
01â 30:29 Jacob said to him, "You yourself know how I have served you, and how your cattle have fared with me.
01â 30:30 For you had little before I came, and it has increased abundantly; and the LORD has blessed you wherever I turned. But now when shall I provide for my own household also?"
01â 30:31 He said, "What shall I give you?" Jacob said, "You shall not give me anything; if you will do this for me, I will again feed your flock and keep it:
01â 30:32 let me pass through all your flock today, removing from it every speckled and spotted sheep and every black lamb, and the spotted and speckled among the goats; and such shall be my wages.
01â 30:33 So my honesty will answer for me later, when you come to look into my wages with you. Every one that is not speckled and spotted among the goats and black among the lambs, if found with me, shall be counted stolen."
01â 30:34 Laban said, "Good! Let it be as you have said."
01â 30:35 But that day Laban removed the male goats that were striped and spotted, and all the female goats that were speckled and spotted, every one that had white on it, and every lamb that was black, and put them in charge of his sons;
01â 30:36 and he set a distance of three days' journey between himself and Jacob, while Jacob was pasturing the rest of Laban's flock.
01â 30:37 Then Jacob took fresh rods of poplar and almond and plane, and peeled white streaks in them, exposing the white of the rods.
01â 30:38 He set the rods that he had peeled in front of the flocks in the troughs, that is, the watering places, where the flocks came to drink. And since they bred when they came to drink,
01â 30:39 the flocks bred in front of the rods, and so the flocks produced young that were striped, speckled, and spotted.
01â 30:40 Jacob separated the lambs, and set the faces of the flocks toward the striped and the completely black animals in the flock of Laban; and he put his own droves apart, and did not put them with Laban's flock.
01â 30:41 Whenever the stronger of the flock were breeding, Jacob laid the rods in the troughs before the eyes of the flock, that they might breed among the rods,
01â 30:42 but for the feebler of the flock he did not lay them there; so the feebler were Laban's, and the stronger Jacob's.
01â 30:43 Thus the man grew exceedingly rich, and had large flocks, and male and female slaves, and camels and donkeys.
01â 31:1 Now Jacob heard that the sons of Laban were saying, "Jacob has taken all that was our father's; he has gained all this wealth from what belonged to our father."
01â 31:2 And Jacob saw that Laban did not regard him as favorably as he did before.
01â 31:3 Then the LORD said to Jacob, "Return to the land of your ancestors and to your kindred, and I will be with you."
01â 31:4 So Jacob sent and called Rachel and Leah into the field where his flock was,
01â 31:5 and said to them, "I see that your father does not regard me as favorably as he did before. But the God of my father has been with me.
01â 31:6 You know that I have served your father with all my strength;
01â 31:7 yet your father has cheated me and changed my wages ten times, but God did not permit him to harm me.
01â 31:8 If he said, 'The speckled shall be your wages,' then all the flock bore speckled; and if he said, 'The striped shall be your wages,' then all the flock bore striped.
01â 31:9 Thus God has taken away the livestock of your father, and given them to me.
01â 31:10 During the mating of the flock I once had a dream in which I looked up and saw that the male goats that leaped upon the flock were striped, speckled, and mottled.
01â 31:11 Then the angel of God said to me in the dream, 'Jacob,' and I said, 'Here I am!'
01â 31:12 And he said, 'Look up and see that all the goats that leap on the flock are striped, speckled, and mottled; for I have seen all that Laban is doing to you.
01â 31:13 I am the God of Bethel, where you anointed a pillar and made a vow to me. Now leave this land at once and return to the land of your birth.'"
01â 31:14 Then Rachel and Leah answered him, "Is there any portion or inheritance left to us in our father's house?
01â 31:15 Are we not regarded by him as foreigners? For he has sold us, and he has been using up the money given for us.
01â 31:16 All the property that God has taken away from our father belongs to us and to our children; now then, do whatever God has said to you."
01â 31:17 So Jacob arose, and set his children and his wives on camels;
01â 31:18 and he drove away all his livestock, all the property that he had gained, the livestock in his possession that he had acquired in Paddan-aram, to go to his father Isaac in the land of Canaan.
01â 31:19 Now Laban had gone to shear his sheep, and Rachel stole her father's household gods.
01â 31:20 And Jacob deceived Laban the Aramean, in that he did not tell him that he intended to flee.
01â 31:21 So he fled with all that he had; starting out he crossed the Euphrates, and set his face toward the hill country of Gilead.
01â 31:22 On the third day Laban was told that Jacob had fled.
01â 31:23 So he took his kinsfolk with him and pursued him for seven days until he caught up with him in the hill country of Gilead.
01â 31:24 But God came to Laban the Aramean in a dream by night, and said to him, "Take heed that you say not a word to Jacob, either good or bad."
01â 31:25 Laban overtook Jacob. Now Jacob had pitched his tent in the hill country, and Laban with his kinsfolk camped in the hill country of Gilead.
01â 31:26 Laban said to Jacob, "What have you done? You have deceived me, and carried away my daughters like captives of the sword.
01â 31:27 Why did you flee secretly and deceive me and not tell me? I would have sent you away with mirth and songs, with tambourine and lyre.
01â 31:28 And why did you not permit me to kiss my sons and my daughters farewell? What you have done is foolish.
01â 31:29 It is in my power to do you harm; but the God of your father spoke to me last night, saying, 'Take heed that you speak to Jacob neither good nor bad.'
01â 31:30 Even though you had to go because you longed greatly for your father's house, why did you steal my gods?"
01â 31:31 Jacob answered Laban, "Because I was afraid, for I thought that you would take your daughters from me by force.
01â 31:32 But anyone with whom you find your gods shall not live. In the presence of our kinsfolk, point out what I have that is yours, and take it." Now Jacob did not know that Rachel had stolen the gods.
01â 31:33 So Laban went into Jacob's tent, and into Leah's tent, and into the tent of the two maids, but he did not find them. And he went out of Leah's tent, and entered Rachel's.
01â 31:34 Now Rachel had taken the household gods and put them in the camel's saddle, and sat on them. Laban felt all about in the tent, but did not find them.
01â 31:35 And she said to her father, "Let not my lord be angry that I cannot rise before you, for the way of women is upon me." So he searched, but did not find the household gods.
01â 31:36 Then Jacob became angry, and upbraided Laban. Jacob said to Laban, "What is my offense? What is my sin, that you have hotly pursued me?
01â 31:37 Although you have felt about through all my goods, what have you found of all your household goods? Set it here before my kinsfolk and your kinsfolk, so that they may decide between us two.
01â 31:38 These twenty years I have been with you; your ewes and your female goats have not miscarried, and I have not eaten the rams of your flocks.
01â 31:39 That which was torn by wild beasts I did not bring to you; I bore the loss of it myself; of my hand you required it, whether stolen by day or stolen by night.
01â 31:40 It was like this with me: by day the heat consumed me, and the cold by night, and my sleep fled from my eyes.
01â 31:41 These twenty years I have been in your house; I served you fourteen years for your two daughters, and six years for your flock, and you have changed my wages ten times.
01â 31:42 If the God of my father, the God of Abraham and the Fear of Isaac, had not been on my side, surely now you would have sent me away empty-handed. God saw my affliction and the labor of my hands, and rebuked you last night."
01â 31:43 Then Laban answered and said to Jacob, "The daughters are my daughters, the children are my children, the flocks are my flocks, and all that you see is mine. But what can I do today about these daughters of mine, or about their children whom they have borne?
01â 31:44 Come now, let us make a covenant, you and I; and let it be a witness between you and me."
01â 31:45 So Jacob took a stone, and set it up as a pillar.
01â 31:46 And Jacob said to his kinsfolk, "Gather stones," and they took stones, and made a heap; and they ate there by the heap.
01â 31:47 Laban called it Jegar-sahadutha: but Jacob called it Galeed.
01â 31:48 Laban said, "This heap is a witness between you and me today." Therefore he called it Galeed,
01â 31:49 and the pillar Mizpah, for he said, "The LORD watch between you and me, when we are absent one from the other.
01â 31:50 If you ill-treat my daughters, or if you take wives in addition to my daughters, though no one else is with us, remember that God is witness between you and me."
01â 31:51 Then Laban said to Jacob, "See this heap and see the pillar, which I have set between you and me.
01â 31:52 This heap is a witness, and the pillar is a witness, that I will not pass beyond this heap to you, and you will not pass beyond this heap and this pillar to me, for harm.
01â 31:53 May the God of Abraham and the God of Nahor"--the God of their father--"judge between us." So Jacob swore by the Fear of his father Isaac,
01â 31:54 and Jacob offered a sacrifice on the height and called his kinsfolk to eat bread; and they ate bread and tarried all night in the hill country.
01â 31:55 Early in the morning Laban rose up, and kissed his grandchildren and his daughters and blessed them; then he departed and returned home.
01â 32:1 Jacob went on his way and the angels of God met him;
01â 32:2 and when Jacob saw them he said, "This is God's camp!" So he called that place Mahanaim.
01â 32:3 Jacob sent messengers before him to his brother Esau in the land of Seir, the country of Edom,
01â 32:4 instructing them, "Thus you shall say to my lord Esau: Thus says your servant Jacob, 'I have lived with Laban as an alien, and stayed until now;
01â 32:5 and I have oxen, donkeys, flocks, male and female slaves; and I have sent to tell my lord, in order that I may find favor in your sight.'"
01â 32:6 The messengers returned to Jacob, saying, "We came to your brother Esau, and he is coming to meet you, and four hundred men are with him."
01â 32:7 Then Jacob was greatly afraid and distressed; and he divided the people that were with him, and the flocks and herds and camels, into two companies,
01â 32:8 thinking, "If Esau comes to the one company and destroys it, then the company that is left will escape."
01â 32:9 And Jacob said, "O God of my father Abraham and God of my father Isaac, O LORD who said to me, 'Return to your country and to your kindred, and I will do you good,'
01â 32:10 I am not worthy of the least of all the steadfast love and all the faithfulness that you have shown to your servant, for with only my staff I crossed this Jordan; and now I have become two companies.
01â 32:11 Deliver me, please, from the hand of my brother, from the hand of Esau, for I am afraid of him; he may come and kill us all, the mothers with the children.
01â 32:12 Yet you have said, 'I will surely do you good, and make your offspring as the sand of the sea, which cannot be counted because of their number.'"
01â 32:13 So he spent that night there, and from what he had with him he took a present for his brother Esau,
01â 32:14 two hundred female goats and twenty male goats, two hundred ewes and twenty rams,
01â 32:15 thirty milch camels and their colts, forty cows and ten bulls, twenty female donkeys and ten male donkeys.
01â 32:16 These he delivered into the hand of his servants, every drove by itself, and said to his servants, "Pass on ahead of me, and put a space between drove and drove."
01â 32:17 He instructed the foremost, "When Esau my brother meets you, and asks you, 'To whom do you belong? Where are you going? And whose are these ahead of you?'
01â 32:18 then you shall say, 'They belong to your servant Jacob; they are a present sent to my lord Esau; and moreover he is behind us.'"
01â 32:19 He likewise instructed the second and the third and all who followed the droves, "You shall say the same thing to Esau when you meet him,
01â 32:20 and you shall say, 'Moreover your servant Jacob is behind us.'" For he thought, "I may appease him with the present that goes ahead of me, and afterwards I shall see his face; perhaps he will accept me."
01â 32:21 So the present passed on ahead of him; and he himself spent that night in the camp.
01â 32:22 The same night he got up and took his two wives, his two maids, and his eleven children, and crossed the ford of the Jabbok.
01â 32:23 He took them and sent them across the stream, and likewise everything that he had.
01â 32:24 Jacob was left alone; and a man wrestled with him until daybreak.
01â 32:25 When the man saw that he did not prevail against Jacob, he struck him on the hip socket; and Jacob's hip was put out of joint as he wrestled with him.
01â 32:26 Then he said, "Let me go, for the day is breaking." But Jacob said, "I will not let you go, unless you bless me."
01â 32:27 So he said to him, "What is your name?" And he said, "Jacob."
01â 32:28 Then the man said, "You shall no longer be called Jacob, but Israel, for you have striven with God and with humans, and have prevailed."
01â 32:29 Then Jacob asked him, "Please tell me your name." But he said, "Why is it that you ask my name?" And there he blessed him.
01â 32:30 So Jacob called the place Peniel, saying, "For I have seen God face to face, and yet my life is preserved."
01â 32:31 The sun rose upon him as he passed Penuel, limping because of his hip.
01â 32:32 Therefore to this day the Israelites do not eat the thigh muscle that is on the hip socket, because he struck Jacob on the hip socket at the thigh muscle.
01â 33:1 Now Jacob looked up and saw Esau coming, and four hundred men with him. So he divided the children among Leah and Rachel and the two maids.
01â 33:2 He put the maids with their children in front, then Leah with her children, and Rachel and Joseph last of all.
01â 33:3 He himself went on ahead of them, bowing himself to the ground seven times, until he came near his brother.
01â 33:4 But Esau ran to meet him, and embraced him, and fell on his neck and kissed him, and they wept.
01â 33:5 When Esau looked up and saw the women and children, he said, "Who are these with you?" Jacob said, "The children whom God has graciously given your servant."
01â 33:6 Then the maids drew near, they and their children, and bowed down;
01â 33:7 Leah likewise and her children drew near and bowed down; and finally Joseph and Rachel drew near, and they bowed down.
01â 33:8 Esau said, "What do you mean by all this company that I met?" Jacob answered, "To find favor with my lord."
01â 33:9 But Esau said, "I have enough, my brother; keep what you have for yourself."
01â 33:10 Jacob said, "No, please; if I find favor with you, then accept my present from my hand; for truly to see your face is like seeing the face of God--since you have received me with such favor.
01â 33:11 Please accept my gift that is brought to you, because God has dealt graciously with me, and because I have everything I want." So he urged him, and he took it.
01â 33:12 Then Esau said, "Let us journey on our way, and I will go alongside you."
01â 33:13 But Jacob said to him, "My lord knows that the children are frail and that the flocks and herds, which are nursing, are a care to me; and if they are overdriven for one day, all the flocks will die.
01â 33:14 Let my lord pass on ahead of his servant, and I will lead on slowly, according to the pace of the cattle that are before me and according to the pace of the children, until I come to my lord in Seir."
01â 33:15 So Esau said, "Let me leave with you some of the people who are with me." But he said, "Why should my lord be so kind to me?"
01â 33:16 So Esau returned that day on his way to Seir.
01â 33:17 But Jacob journeyed to Succoth, and built himself a house, and made booths for his cattle; therefore the place is called Succoth.
01â 33:18 Jacob came safely to the city of Shechem, which is in the land of Canaan, on his way from Paddan-aram; and he camped before the city.
01â 33:19 And from the sons of Hamor, Shechem's father, he bought for one hundred pieces of money the plot of land on which he had pitched his tent.
01â 33:20 There he erected an altar and called it El-Elohe-Israel.
01â 34:1 Now Dinah the daughter of Leah, whom she had borne to Jacob, went out to visit the women of the region.
01â 34:2 When Shechem son of Hamor the Hivite, prince of the region, saw her, he seized her and lay with her by force.
01â 34:3 And his soul was drawn to Dinah daughter of Jacob; he loved the girl, and spoke tenderly to her.
01â 34:4 So Shechem spoke to his father Hamor, saying, "Get me this girl to be my wife."
01â 34:5 Now Jacob heard that Shechem had defiled his daughter Dinah; but his sons were with his cattle in the field, so Jacob held his peace until they came.
01â 34:6 And Hamor the father of Shechem went out to Jacob to speak with him,
01â 34:7 just as the sons of Jacob came in from the field. When they heard of it, the men were indignant and very angry, because he had committed an outrage in Israel by lying with Jacob's daughter, for such a thing ought not to be done.
01â 34:8 But Hamor spoke with them, saying, "The heart of my son Shechem longs for your daughter; please give her to him in marriage.
01â 34:9 Make marriages with us; give your daughters to us, and take our daughters for yourselves.
01â 34:10 You shall live with us; and the land shall be open to you; live and trade in it, and get property in it."
01â 34:11 Shechem also said to her father and to her brothers, "Let me find favor with you, and whatever you say to me I will give.
01â 34:12 Put the marriage present and gift as high as you like, and I will give whatever you ask me; only give me the girl to be my wife."
01â 34:13 The sons of Jacob answered Shechem and his father Hamor deceitfully, because he had defiled their sister Dinah.
01â 34:14 They said to them, "We cannot do this thing, to give our sister to one who is uncircumcised, for that would be a disgrace to us.
01â 34:15 Only on this condition will we consent to you: that you will become as we are and every male among you be circumcised.
01â 34:16 Then we will give our daughters to you, and we will take your daughters for ourselves, and we will live among you and become one people.
01â 34:17 But if you will not listen to us and be circumcised, then we will take our daughter and be gone."
01â 34:18 Their words pleased Hamor and Hamor's son Shechem.
01â 34:19 And the young man did not delay to do the thing, because he was delighted with Jacob's daughter. Now he was the most honored of all his family.
01â 34:20 So Hamor and his son Shechem came to the gate of their city and spoke to the men of their city, saying,
01â 34:21 "These people are friendly with us; let them live in the land and trade in it, for the land is large enough for them; let us take their daughters in marriage, and let us give them our daughters.
01â 34:22 Only on this condition will they agree to live among us, to become one people: that every male among us be circumcised as they are circumcised.
01â 34:23 Will not their livestock, their property, and all their animals be ours? Only let us agree with them, and they will live among us."
01â 34:24 And all who went out of the city gate heeded Hamor and his son Shechem; and every male was circumcised, all who went out of the gate of his city.
01â 34:25 On the third day, when they were still in pain, two of the sons of Jacob, Simeon and Levi, Dinah's brothers, took their swords and came against the city unawares, and killed all the males.
01â 34:26 They killed Hamor and his son Shechem with the sword, and took Dinah out of Shechem's house, and went away.
01â 34:27 And the other sons of Jacob came upon the slain, and plundered the city, because their sister had been defiled.
01â 34:28 They took their flocks and their herds, their donkeys, and whatever was in the city and in the field.
01â 34:29 All their wealth, all their little ones and their wives, all that was in the houses, they captured and made their prey.
01â 34:30 Then Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, "You have brought trouble on me by making me odious to the inhabitants of the land, the Canaanites and the Perizzites; my numbers are few, and if they gather themselves against me and attack me, I shall be destroyed, both I and my household."
01â 34:31 But they said, "Should our sister be treated like a whore?"
01â 35:1 God said to Jacob, "Arise, go up to Bethel, and settle there. Make an altar there to the God who appeared to you when you fled from your brother Esau."
01â 35:2 So Jacob said to his household and to all who were with him, "Put away the foreign gods that are among you, and purify yourselves, and change your clothes;
01â 35:3 then come, let us go up to Bethel, that I may make an altar there to the God who answered me in the day of my distress and has been with me wherever I have gone."
01â 35:4 So they gave to Jacob all the foreign gods that they had, and the rings that were in their ears; and Jacob hid them under the oak that was near Shechem.
01â 35:5 As they journeyed, a terror from God fell upon the cities all around them, so that no one pursued them.
01â 35:6 Jacob came to Luz (that is, Bethel), which is in the land of Canaan, he and all the people who were with him,
01â 35:7 and there he built an altar and called the place El-bethel, because it was there that God had revealed himself to him when he fled from his brother.
01â 35:8 And Deborah, Rebekah's nurse, died, and she was buried under an oak below Bethel. So it was called Allon-bacuth.
01â 35:9 God appeared to Jacob again when he came from Paddan-aram, and he blessed him.
01â 35:10 God said to him, "Your name is Jacob; no longer shall you be called Jacob, but Israel shall be your name." So he was called Israel.
01â 35:11 God said to him, "I am God Almighty: be fruitful and multiply; a nation and a company of nations shall come from you, and kings shall spring from you.
01â 35:12 The land that I gave to Abraham and Isaac I will give to you, and I will give the land to your offspring after you."
01â 35:13 Then God went up from him at the place where he had spoken with him.
01â 35:14 Jacob set up a pillar in the place where he had spoken with him, a pillar of stone; and he poured out a drink offering on it, and poured oil on it.
01â 35:15 So Jacob called the place where God had spoken with him Bethel.
01â 35:16 Then they journeyed from Bethel; and when they were still some distance from Ephrath, Rachel was in childbirth, and she had hard labor.
01â 35:17 When she was in her hard labor, the midwife said to her, "Do not be afraid; for now you will have another son."
01â 35:18 As her soul was departing (for she died), she named him Ben-oni; but his father called him Benjamin.
01â 35:19 So Rachel died, and she was buried on the way to Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem),
01â 35:20 and Jacob set up a pillar at her grave; it is the pillar of Rachel's tomb, which is there to this day.
01â 35:21 Israel journeyed on, and pitched his tent beyond the tower of Eder.
01â 35:22 While Israel lived in that land, Reuben went and lay with Bilhah his father's concubine; and Israel heard of it. Now the sons of Jacob were twelve.
01â 35:23 The sons of Leah: Reuben (Jacob's firstborn), Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun.
01â 35:24 The sons of Rachel: Joseph and Benjamin.
01â 35:25 The sons of Bilhah, Rachel's maid: Dan and Naphtali.
01â 35:26 The sons of Zilpah, Leah's maid: Gad and Asher. These were the sons of Jacob who were born to him in Paddan-aram.
01â 35:27 Jacob came to his father Isaac at Mamre, or Kiriath-arba (that is, Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had resided as aliens.
01â 35:28 Now the days of Isaac were one hundred eighty years.
01â 35:29 And Isaac breathed his last; he died and was gathered to his people, old and full of days; and his sons Esau and Jacob buried him.
01â 36:1 These are the descendants of Esau (that is, Edom).
01â 36:2 Esau took his wives from the Canaanites: Adah daughter of Elon the Hittite, Oholibamah daughter of Anah son of Zibeon the Hivite,
01â 36:3 and Basemath, Ishmael's daughter, sister of Nebaioth.
01â 36:4 Adah bore Eliphaz to Esau; Basemath bore Reuel;
01â 36:5 and Oholibamah bore Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These are the sons of Esau who were born to him in the land of Canaan.
01â 36:6 Then Esau took his wives, his sons, his daughters, and all the members of his household, his cattle, all his livestock, and all the property he had acquired in the land of Canaan; and he moved to a land some distance from his brother Jacob.
01â 36:7 For their possessions were too great for them to live together; the land where they were staying could not support them because of their livestock.
01â 36:8 So Esau settled in the hill country of Seir; Esau is Edom.
01â 36:9 These are the descendants of Esau, ancestor of the Edomites, in the hill country of Seir.
01â 36:10 These are the names of Esau's sons: Eliphaz son of Adah the wife of Esau; Reuel, the son of Esau's wife Basemath.
01â 36:11 The sons of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz.
01â 36:12 (Timna was a concubine of Eliphaz, Esau's son; she bore Amalek to Eliphaz.) These were the sons of Adah, Esau's wife.
01â 36:13 These were the sons of Reuel: Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah. These were the sons of Esau's wife, Basemath.
01â 36:14 These were the sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah, daughter of Anah son of Zibeon: she bore to Esau Jeush, Jalam, and Korah.
01â 36:15 These are the clans of the sons of Esau. The sons of Eliphaz the firstborn of Esau: the clans Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz,
01â 36:16 Korah, Gatam, and Amalek; these are the clans of Eliphaz in the land of Edom; they are the sons of Adah.
01â 36:17 These are the sons of Esau's son Reuel: the clans Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah; these are the clans of Reuel in the land of Edom; they are the sons of Esau's wife Basemath.
01â 36:18 These are the sons of Esau's wife Oholibamah: the clans Jeush, Jalam, and Korah; these are the clans born of Esau's wife Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah.
01â 36:19 These are the sons of Esau (that is, Edom), and these are their clans.
01â 36:20 These are the sons of Seir the Horite, the inhabitants of the land: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01â 36:21 Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan; these are the clans of the Horites, the sons of Seir in the land of Edom.
01â 36:22 The sons of Lotan were Hori and Heman; and Lotan's sister was Timna.
01â 36:23 These are the sons of Shobal: Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and Onam.
01â 36:24 These are the sons of Zibeon: Aiah and Anah; he is the Anah who found the springs in the wilderness, as he pastured the donkeys of his father Zibeon.
01â 36:25 These are the children of Anah: Dishon and Oholibamah daughter of Anah.
01â 36:26 These are the sons of Dishon: Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran, and Cheran.
01â 36:27 These are the sons of Ezer: Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan.
01â 36:28 These are the sons of Dishan: Uz and Aran.
01â 36:29 These are the clans of the Horites: the clans Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah,
01â 36:30 Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan; these are the clans of the Horites, clan by clan in the land of Seir.
01â 36:31 These are the kings who reigned in the land of Edom, before any king reigned over the Israelites.
01â 36:32 Bela son of Beor reigned in Edom, the name of his city being Dinhabah.
01â 36:33 Bela died, and Jobab son of Zerah of Bozrah succeeded him as king.
01â 36:34 Jobab died, and Husham of the land of the Temanites succeeded him as king.
01â 36:35 Husham died, and Hadad son of Bedad, who defeated Midian in the country of Moab, succeeded him as king, the name of his city being Avith.
01â 36:36 Hadad died, and Samlah of Masrekah succeeded him as king.
01â 36:37 Samlah died, and Shaul of Rehoboth on the Euphrates succeeded him as king.
01â 36:38 Shaul died, and Baal-hanan son of Achbor succeeded him as king.
01â 36:39 Baal-hanan son of Achbor died, and Hadar succeeded him as king, the name of his city being Pau; his wife's name was Mehetabel, the daughter of Matred, daughter of Me-zahab.
01â 36:40 These are the names of the clans of Esau, according to their families and their localities by their names: the clans Timna, Alvah, Jetheth,
01â 36:41 Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon,
01â 36:42 Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar,
01â 36:43 Magdiel, and Iram; these are the clans of Edom (that is, Esau, the father of Edom), according to their settlements in the land that they held.
01â 37:1 Jacob settled in the land where his father had lived as an alien, the land of Canaan.
01â 37:2 This is the story of the family of Jacob. Joseph, being seventeen years old, was shepherding the flock with his brothers; he was a helper to the sons of Bilhah and Zilpah, his father's wives; and Joseph brought a bad report of them to their father.
01â 37:3 Now Israel loved Joseph more than any other of his children, because he was the son of his old age; and he had made him a long robe with sleeves.
01â 37:4 But when his brothers saw that their father loved him more than all his brothers, they hated him, and could not speak peaceably to him.
01â 37:5 Once Joseph had a dream, and when he told it to his brothers, they hated him even more.
01â 37:6 He said to them, "Listen to this dream that I dreamed.
01â 37:7 There we were, binding sheaves in the field. Suddenly my sheaf rose and stood upright; then your sheaves gathered around it, and bowed down to my sheaf."
01â 37:8 His brothers said to him, "Are you indeed to reign over us? Are you indeed to have dominion over us?" So they hated him even more because of his dreams and his words.
01â 37:9 He had another dream, and told it to his brothers, saying, "Look, I have had another dream: the sun, the moon, and eleven stars were bowing down to me."
01â 37:10 But when he told it to his father and to his brothers, his father rebuked him, and said to him, "What kind of dream is this that you have had? Shall we indeed come, I and your mother and your brothers, and bow to the ground before you?"
01â 37:11 So his brothers were jealous of him, but his father kept the matter in mind.
01â 37:12 Now his brothers went to pasture their father's flock near Shechem.
01â 37:13 And Israel said to Joseph, "Are not your brothers pasturing the flock at Shechem? Come, I will send you to them." He answered, "Here I am."
01â 37:14 So he said to him, "Go now, see if it is well with your brothers and with the flock; and bring word back to me." So he sent him from the valley of Hebron. He came to Shechem,
01â 37:15 and a man found him wandering in the fields; the man asked him, "What are you seeking?"
01â 37:16 "I am seeking my brothers," he said; "tell me, please, where they are pasturing the flock."
01â 37:17 The man said, "They have gone away, for I heard them say, 'Let us go to Dothan.'" So Joseph went after his brothers, and found them at Dothan.
01â 37:18 They saw him from a distance, and before he came near to them, they conspired to kill him.
01â 37:19 They said to one another, "Here comes this dreamer.
01â 37:20 Come now, let us kill him and throw him into one of the pits; then we shall say that a wild animal has devoured him, and we shall see what will become of his dreams."
01â 37:21 But when Reuben heard it, he delivered him out of their hands, saying, "Let us not take his life."
01â 37:22 Reuben said to them, "Shed no blood; throw him into this pit here in the wilderness, but lay no hand on him"--that he might rescue him out of their hand and restore him to his father.
01â 37:23 So when Joseph came to his brothers, they stripped him of his robe, the long robe with sleeves that he wore;
01â 37:24 and they took him and threw him into a pit. The pit was empty; there was no water in it.
01â 37:25 Then they sat down to eat; and looking up they saw a caravan of Ishmaelites coming from Gilead, with their camels carrying gum, balm, and resin, on their way to carry it down to Egypt.
01â 37:26 Then Judah said to his brothers, "What profit is it if we kill our brother and conceal his blood?
01â 37:27 Come, let us sell him to the Ishmaelites, and not lay our hands on him, for he is our brother, our own flesh." And his brothers agreed.
01â 37:28 When some Midianite traders passed by, they drew Joseph up, lifting him out of the pit, and sold him to the Ishmaelites for twenty pieces of silver. And they took Joseph to Egypt.
01â 37:29 When Reuben returned to the pit and saw that Joseph was not in the pit, he tore his clothes.
01â 37:30 He returned to his brothers, and said, "The boy is gone; and I, where can I turn?"
01â 37:31 Then they took Joseph's robe, slaughtered a goat, and dipped the robe in the blood.
01â 37:32 They had the long robe with sleeves taken to their father, and they said, "This we have found; see now whether it is your son's robe or not."
01â 37:33 He recognized it, and said, "It is my son's robe! A wild animal has devoured him; Joseph is without doubt torn to pieces."
01â 37:34 Then Jacob tore his garments, and put sackcloth on his loins, and mourned for his son many days.
01â 37:35 All his sons and all his daughters sought to comfort him; but he refused to be comforted, and said, "No, I shall go down to Sheol to my son, mourning." Thus his father bewailed him.
01â 37:36 Meanwhile the Midianites had sold him in Egypt to Potiphar, one of Pharaoh's officials, the captain of the guard.
01â 38:1 It happened at that time that Judah went down from his brothers and settled near a certain Adullamite whose name was Hirah.
01â 38:2 There Judah saw the daughter of a certain Canaanite whose name was Shua; he married her and went in to her.
01â 38:3 She conceived and bore a son; and he named him Er.
01â 38:4 Again she conceived and bore a son whom she named Onan.
01â 38:5 Yet again she bore a son, and she named him Shelah. She was in Chezib when she bore him.
01â 38:6 Judah took a wife for Er his firstborn; her name was Tamar.
01â 38:7 But Er, Judah's firstborn, was wicked in the sight of the LORD, and the LORD put him to death.
01â 38:8 Then Judah said to Onan, "Go in to your brother's wife and perform the duty of a brother-in-law to her; raise up offspring for your brother."
01â 38:9 But since Onan knew that the offspring would not be his, he spilled his semen on the ground whenever he went in to his brother's wife, so that he would not give offspring to his brother.
01â 38:10 What he did was displeasing in the sight of the LORD, and he put him to death also.
01â 38:11 Then Judah said to his daughter-in-law Tamar, "Remain a widow in your father's house until my son Shelah grows up"--for he feared that he too would die, like his brothers. So Tamar went to live in her father's house.
01â 38:12 In course of time the wife of Judah, Shua's daughter, died; when Judah's time of mourning was over, he went up to Timnah to his sheepshearers, he and his friend Hirah the Adullamite.
01â 38:13 When Tamar was told, "Your father-in-law is going up to Timnah to shear his sheep,"
01â 38:14 she put off her widow's garments, put on a veil, wrapped herself up, and sat down at the entrance to Enaim, which is on the road to Timnah. She saw that Shelah was grown up, yet she had not been given to him in marriage.
01â 38:15 When Judah saw her, he thought her to be a prostitute, for she had covered her face.
01â 38:16 He went over to her at the road side, and said, "Come, let me come in to you," for he did not know that she was his daughter-in-law. She said, "What will you give me, that you may come in to me?"
01â 38:17 He answered, "I will send you a kid from the flock." And she said, "Only if you give me a pledge, until you send it."
01â 38:18 He said, "What pledge shall I give you?" She replied, "Your signet and your cord, and the staff that is in your hand." So he gave them to her, and went in to her, and she conceived by him.
01â 38:19 Then she got up and went away, and taking off her veil she put on the garments of her widowhood.
01â 38:20 When Judah sent the kid by his friend the Adullamite, to recover the pledge from the woman, he could not find her.
01â 38:21 He asked the townspeople, "Where is the temple prostitute who was at Enaim by the wayside?" But they said, "No prostitute has been here."
01â 38:22 So he returned to Judah, and said, "I have not found her; moreover the townspeople said, 'No prostitute has been here.'"
01â 38:23 Judah replied, "Let her keep the things as her own, otherwise we will be laughed at; you see, I sent this kid, and you could not find her."
01â 38:24 About three months later Judah was told, "Your daughter-in-law Tamar has played the whore; moreover she is pregnant as a result of whoredom." And Judah said, "Bring her out, and let her be burned."
01â 38:25 As she was being brought out, she sent word to her father-in-law, "It was the owner of these who made me pregnant." And she said, "Take note, please, whose these are, the signet and the cord and the staff."
01â 38:26 Then Judah acknowledged them and said, "She is more in the right than I, since I did not give her to my son Shelah." And he did not lie with her again.
01â 38:27 When the time of her delivery came, there were twins in her womb.
01â 38:28 While she was in labor, one put out a hand; and the midwife took and bound on his hand a crimson thread, saying, "This one came out first."
01â 38:29 But just then he drew back his hand, and out came his brother; and she said, "What a breach you have made for yourself!" Therefore he was named Perez.
01â 38:30 Afterward his brother came out with the crimson thread on his hand; and he was named Zerah.
01â 39:1 Now Joseph was taken down to Egypt, and Potiphar, an officer of Pharaoh, the captain of the guard, an Egyptian, bought him from the Ishmaelites who had brought him down there.
01â 39:2 The LORD was with Joseph, and he became a successful man; he was in the house of his Egyptian master.
01â 39:3 His master saw that the LORD was with him, and that the LORD caused all that he did to prosper in his hands.
01â 39:4 So Joseph found favor in his sight and attended him; he made him overseer of his house and put him in charge of all that he had.
01â 39:5 From the time that he made him overseer in his house and over all that he had, the LORD blessed the Egyptian's house for Joseph's sake; the blessing of the LORD was on all that he had, in house and field.
01â 39:6 So he left all that he had in Joseph's charge; and, with him there, he had no concern for anything but the food that he ate. Now Joseph was handsome and good-looking.
01â 39:7 And after a time his master's wife cast her eyes on Joseph and said, "Lie with me."
01â 39:8 But he refused and said to his master's wife, "Look, with me here, my master has no concern about anything in the house, and he has put everything that he has in my hand.
01â 39:9 He is not greater in this house than I am, nor has he kept back anything from me except yourself, because you are his wife. How then could I do this great wickedness, and sin against God?"
01â 39:10 And although she spoke to Joseph day after day, he would not consent to lie beside her or to be with her.
01â 39:11 One day, however, when he went into the house to do his work, and while no one else was in the house,
01â 39:12 she caught hold of his garment, saying, "Lie with me!" But he left his garment in her hand, and fled and ran outside.
01â 39:13 When she saw that he had left his garment in her hand and had fled outside,
01â 39:14 she called out to the members of her household and said to them, "See, my husband has brought among us a Hebrew to insult us! He came in to me to lie with me, and I cried out with a loud voice;
01â 39:15 and when he heard me raise my voice and cry out, he left his garment beside me, and fled outside."
01â 39:16 Then she kept his garment by her until his master came home,
01â 39:17 and she told him the same story, saying, "The Hebrew servant, whom you have brought among us, came in to me to insult me;
01â 39:18 but as soon as I raised my voice and cried out, he left his garment beside me, and fled outside."
01â 39:19 When his master heard the words that his wife spoke to him, saying, "This is the way your servant treated me," he became enraged.
01â 39:20 And Joseph's master took him and put him into the prison, the place where the king's prisoners were confined; he remained there in prison.
01â 39:21 But the LORD was with Joseph and showed him steadfast love; he gave him favor in the sight of the chief jailer.
01â 39:22 The chief jailer committed to Joseph's care all the prisoners who were in the prison, and whatever was done there, he was the one who did it.
01â 39:23 The chief jailer paid no heed to anything that was in Joseph's care, because the LORD was with him; and whatever he did, the LORD made it prosper.
01â 40:1 Some time after this, the cupbearer of the king of Egypt and his baker offended their lord the king of Egypt.
01â 40:2 Pharaoh was angry with his two officers, the chief cupbearer and the chief baker,
01â 40:3 and he put them in custody in the house of the captain of the guard, in the prison where Joseph was confined.
01â 40:4 The captain of the guard charged Joseph with them, and he waited on them; and they continued for some time in custody.
01â 40:5 One night they both dreamed--the cupbearer and the baker of the king of Egypt, who were confined in the prison--each his own dream, and each dream with its own meaning.
01â 40:6 When Joseph came to them in the morning, he saw that they were troubled.
01â 40:7 So he asked Pharaoh's officers, who were with him in custody in his master's house, "Why are your faces downcast today?"
01â 40:8 They said to him, "We have had dreams, and there is no one to interpret them." And Joseph said to them, "Do not interpretations belong to God? Please tell them to me."
01â 40:9 So the chief cupbearer told his dream to Joseph, and said to him, "In my dream there was a vine before me,
01â 40:10 and on the vine there were three branches. As soon as it budded, its blossoms came out and the clusters ripened into grapes.
01â 40:11 Pharaoh's cup was in my hand; and I took the grapes and pressed them into Pharaoh's cup, and placed the cup in Pharaoh's hand."
01â 40:12 Then Joseph said to him, "This is its interpretation: the three branches are three days;
01â 40:13 within three days Pharaoh will lift up your head and restore you to your office; and you shall place Pharaoh's cup in his hand, just as you used to do when you were his cupbearer.
01â 40:14 But remember me when it is well with you; please do me the kindness to make mention of me to Pharaoh, and so get me out of this place.
01â 40:15 For in fact I was stolen out of the land of the Hebrews; and here also I have done nothing that they should have put me into the dungeon."
01â 40:16 When the chief baker saw that the interpretation was favorable, he said to Joseph, "I also had a dream: there were three cake baskets on my head,
01â 40:17 and in the uppermost basket there were all sorts of baked food for Pharaoh, but the birds were eating it out of the basket on my head."
01â 40:18 And Joseph answered, "This is its interpretation: the three baskets are three days;
01â 40:19 within three days Pharaoh will lift up your head--from you!--and hang you on a pole; and the birds will eat the flesh from you."
01â 40:20 On the third day, which was Pharaoh's birthday, he made a feast for all his servants, and lifted up the head of the chief cupbearer and the head of the chief baker among his servants.
01â 40:21 He restored the chief cupbearer to his cupbearing, and he placed the cup in Pharaoh's hand;
01â 40:22 but the chief baker he hanged, just as Joseph had interpreted to them.
01â 40:23 Yet the chief cupbearer did not remember Joseph, but forgot him.
01â 41:1 After two whole years, Pharaoh dreamed that he was standing by the Nile,
01â 41:2 and there came up out of the Nile seven sleek and fat cows, and they grazed in the reed grass.
01â 41:3 Then seven other cows, ugly and thin, came up out of the Nile after them, and stood by the other cows on the bank of the Nile.
01â 41:4 The ugly and thin cows ate up the seven sleek and fat cows. And Pharaoh awoke.
01â 41:5 Then he fell asleep and dreamed a second time; seven ears of grain, plump and good, were growing on one stalk.
01â 41:6 Then seven ears, thin and blighted by the east wind, sprouted after them.
01â 41:7 The thin ears swallowed up the seven plump and full ears. Pharaoh awoke, and it was a dream.
01â 41:8 In the morning his spirit was troubled; so he sent and called for all the magicians of Egypt and all its wise men. Pharaoh told them his dreams, but there was no one who could interpret them to Pharaoh.
01â 41:9 Then the chief cupbearer said to Pharaoh, "I remember my faults today.
01â 41:10 Once Pharaoh was angry with his servants, and put me and the chief baker in custody in the house of the captain of the guard.
01â 41:11 We dreamed on the same night, he and I, each having a dream with its own meaning.
01â 41:12 A young Hebrew was there with us, a servant of the captain of the guard. When we told him, he interpreted our dreams to us, giving an interpretation to each according to his dream.
01â 41:13 As he interpreted to us, so it turned out; I was restored to my office, and the baker was hanged."
01â 41:14 Then Pharaoh sent for Joseph, and he was hurriedly brought out of the dungeon. When he had shaved himself and changed his clothes, he came in before Pharaoh.
01â 41:15 And Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I have had a dream, and there is no one who can interpret it. I have heard it said of you that when you hear a dream you can interpret it."
01â 41:16 Joseph answered Pharaoh, "It is not I; God will give Pharaoh a favorable answer."
01â 41:17 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "In my dream I was standing on the banks of the Nile;
01â 41:18 and seven cows, fat and sleek, came up out of the Nile and fed in the reed grass.
01â 41:19 Then seven other cows came up after them, poor, very ugly, and thin. Never had I seen such ugly ones in all the land of Egypt.
01â 41:20 The thin and ugly cows ate up the first seven fat cows,
01â 41:21 but when they had eaten them no one would have known that they had done so, for they were still as ugly as before. Then I awoke.
01â 41:22 I fell asleep a second time and I saw in my dream seven ears of grain, full and good, growing on one stalk,
01â 41:23 and seven ears, withered, thin, and blighted by the east wind, sprouting after them;
01â 41:24 and the thin ears swallowed up the seven good ears. But when I told it to the magicians, there was no one who could explain it to me."
01â 41:25 Then Joseph said to Pharaoh, "Pharaoh's dreams are one and the same; God has revealed to Pharaoh what he is about to do.
01â 41:26 The seven good cows are seven years, and the seven good ears are seven years; the dreams are one.
01â 41:27 The seven lean and ugly cows that came up after them are seven years, as are the seven empty ears blighted by the east wind. They are seven years of famine.
01â 41:28 It is as I told Pharaoh; God has shown to Pharaoh what he is about to do.
01â 41:29 There will come seven years of great plenty throughout all the land of Egypt.
01â 41:30 After them there will arise seven years of famine, and all the plenty will be forgotten in the land of Egypt; the famine will consume the land.
01â 41:31 The plenty will no longer be known in the land because of the famine that will follow, for it will be very grievous.
01â 41:32 And the doubling of Pharaoh's dream means that the thing is fixed by God, and God will shortly bring it about.
01â 41:33 Now therefore let Pharaoh select a man who is discerning and wise, and set him over the land of Egypt.
01â 41:34 Let Pharaoh proceed to appoint overseers over the land, and take one-fifth of the produce of the land of Egypt during the seven plenteous years.
01â 41:35 Let them gather all the food of these good years that are coming, and lay up grain under the authority of Pharaoh for food in the cities, and let them keep it.
01â 41:36 That food shall be a reserve for the land against the seven years of famine that are to befall the land of Egypt, so that the land may not perish through the famine."
01â 41:37 The proposal pleased Pharaoh and all his servants.
01â 41:38 Pharaoh said to his servants, "Can we find anyone else like this--one in whom is the spirit of God?"
01â 41:39 So Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Since God has shown you all this, there is no one so discerning and wise as you.
01â 41:40 You shall be over my house, and all my people shall order themselves as you command; only with regard to the throne will I be greater than you."
01â 41:41 And Pharaoh said to Joseph, "See, I have set you over all the land of Egypt."
01â 41:42 Removing his signet ring from his hand, Pharaoh put it on Joseph's hand; he arrayed him in garments of fine linen, and put a gold chain around his neck.
01â 41:43 He had him ride in the chariot of his second-in-command; and they cried out in front of him, "Bow the knee!" Thus he set him over all the land of Egypt.
01â 41:44 Moreover Pharaoh said to Joseph, "I am Pharaoh, and without your consent no one shall lift up hand or foot in all the land of Egypt."
01â 41:45 Pharaoh gave Joseph the name Zaphenath-paneah; and he gave him Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest of On, as his wife. Thus Joseph gained authority over the land of Egypt.
01â 41:46 Joseph was thirty years old when he entered the service of Pharaoh king of Egypt. And Joseph went out from the presence of Pharaoh, and went through all the land of Egypt.
01â 41:47 During the seven plenteous years the earth produced abundantly.
01â 41:48 He gathered up all the food of the seven years when there was plenty in the land of Egypt, and stored up food in the cities; he stored up in every city the food from the fields around it.
01â 41:49 So Joseph stored up grain in such abundance--like the sand of the sea--that he stopped measuring it; it was beyond measure.
01â 41:50 Before the years of famine came, Joseph had two sons, whom Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest of On, bore to him.
01â 41:51 Joseph named the firstborn Manasseh, "For," he said, "God has made me forget all my hardship and all my father's house."
01â 41:52 The second he named Ephraim, "For God has made me fruitful in the land of my misfortunes."
01â 41:53 The seven years of plenty that prevailed in the land of Egypt came to an end;
01â 41:54 and the seven years of famine began to come, just as Joseph had said. There was famine in every country, but throughout the land of Egypt there was bread.
01â 41:55 When all the land of Egypt was famished, the people cried to Pharaoh for bread. Pharaoh said to all the Egyptians, "Go to Joseph; what he says to you, do."
01â 41:56 And since the famine had spread over all the land, Joseph opened all the storehouses, and sold to the Egyptians, for the famine was severe in the land of Egypt.
01â 41:57 Moreover, all the world came to Joseph in Egypt to buy grain, because the famine became severe throughout the world.
01â 42:1 When Jacob learned that there was grain in Egypt, he said to his sons, "Why do you keep looking at one another?
01â 42:2 I have heard," he said, "that there is grain in Egypt; go down and buy grain for us there, that we may live and not die."
01â 42:3 So ten of Joseph's brothers went down to buy grain in Egypt.
01â 42:4 But Jacob did not send Joseph's brother Benjamin with his brothers, for he feared that harm might come to him.
01â 42:5 Thus the sons of Israel were among the other people who came to buy grain, for the famine had reached the land of Canaan.
01â 42:6 Now Joseph was governor over the land; it was he who sold to all the people of the land. And Joseph's brothers came and bowed themselves before him with their faces to the ground.
01â 42:7 When Joseph saw his brothers, he recognized them, but he treated them like strangers and spoke harshly to them. "Where do you come from?" he said. They said, "From the land of Canaan, to buy food."
01â 42:8 Although Joseph had recognized his brothers, they did not recognize him.
01â 42:9 Joseph also remembered the dreams that he had dreamed about them. He said to them, "You are spies; you have come to see the nakedness of the land!"
01â 42:10 They said to him, "No, my lord; your servants have come to buy food.
01â 42:11 We are all sons of one man; we are honest men; your servants have never been spies."
01â 42:12 But he said to them, "No, you have come to see the nakedness of the land!"
01â 42:13 They said, "We, your servants, are twelve brothers, the sons of a certain man in the land of Canaan; the youngest, however, is now with our father, and one is no more."
01â 42:14 But Joseph said to them, "It is just as I have said to you; you are spies!
01â 42:15 Here is how you shall be tested: as Pharaoh lives, you shall not leave this place unless your youngest brother comes here!
01â 42:16 Let one of you go and bring your brother, while the rest of you remain in prison, in order that your words may be tested, whether there is truth in you; or else, as Pharaoh lives, surely you are spies."
01â 42:17 And he put them all together in prison for three days.
01â 42:18 On the third day Joseph said to them, "Do this and you will live, for I fear God:
01â 42:19 if you are honest men, let one of your brothers stay here where you are imprisoned. The rest of you shall go and carry grain for the famine of your households,
01â 42:20 and bring your youngest brother to me. Thus your words will be verified, and you shall not die." And they agreed to do so.
01â 42:21 They said to one another, "Alas, we are paying the penalty for what we did to our brother; we saw his anguish when he pleaded with us, but we would not listen. That is why this anguish has come upon us."
01â 42:22 Then Reuben answered them, "Did I not tell you not to wrong the boy? But you would not listen. So now there comes a reckoning for his blood."
01â 42:23 They did not know that Joseph understood them, since he spoke with them through an interpreter.
01â 42:24 He turned away from them and wept; then he returned and spoke to them. And he picked out Simeon and had him bound before their eyes.
01â 42:25 Joseph then gave orders to fill their bags with grain, to return every man's money to his sack, and to give them provisions for their journey. This was done for them.
01â 42:26 They loaded their donkeys with their grain, and departed.
01â 42:27 When one of them opened his sack to give his donkey fodder at the lodging place, he saw his money at the top of the sack.
01â 42:28 He said to his brothers, "My money has been put back; here it is in my sack!" At this they lost heart and turned trembling to one another, saying, "What is this that God has done to us?"
01â 42:29 When they came to their father Jacob in the land of Canaan, they told him all that had happened to them, saying,
01â 42:30 "The man, the lord of the land, spoke harshly to us, and charged us with spying on the land.
01â 42:31 But we said to him, 'We are honest men, we are not spies.
01â 42:32 We are twelve brothers, sons of our father; one is no more, and the youngest is now with our father in the land of Canaan.'
01â 42:33 Then the man, the lord of the land, said to us, 'By this I shall know that you are honest men: leave one of your brothers with me, take grain for the famine of your households, and go your way.
01â 42:34 Bring your youngest brother to me, and I shall know that you are not spies but honest men. Then I will release your brother to you, and you may trade in the land.'"
01â 42:35 As they were emptying their sacks, there in each one's sack was his bag of money. When they and their father saw their bundles of money, they were dismayed.
01â 42:36 And their father Jacob said to them, "I am the one you have bereaved of children: Joseph is no more, and Simeon is no more, and now you would take Benjamin. All this has happened to me!"
01â 42:37 Then Reuben said to his father, "You may kill my two sons if I do not bring him back to you. Put him in my hands, and I will bring him back to you."
01â 42:38 But he said, "My son shall not go down with you, for his brother is dead, and he alone is left. If harm should come to him on the journey that you are to make, you would bring down my gray hairs with sorrow to Sheol."
01â 43:1 Now the famine was severe in the land.
01â 43:2 And when they had eaten up the grain that they had brought from Egypt, their father said to them, "Go again, buy us a little more food."
01â 43:3 But Judah said to him, "The man solemnly warned us, saying, 'You shall not see my face unless your brother is with you.'
01â 43:4 If you will send our brother with us, we will go down and buy you food;
01â 43:5 but if you will not send him, we will not go down, for the man said to us, 'You shall not see my face, unless your brother is with you.'"
01â 43:6 Israel said, "Why did you treat me so badly as to tell the man that you had another brother?"
01â 43:7 They replied, "The man questioned us carefully about ourselves and our kindred, saying, 'Is your father still alive? Have you another brother?' What we told him was in answer to these questions. Could we in any way know that he would say, 'Bring your brother down'?"
01â 43:8 Then Judah said to his father Israel, "Send the boy with me, and let us be on our way, so that we may live and not die--you and we and also our little ones.
01â 43:9 I myself will be surety for him; you can hold me accountable for him. If I do not bring him back to you and set him before you, then let me bear the blame forever.
01â 43:10 If we had not delayed, we would now have returned twice."
01â 43:11 Then their father Israel said to them, "If it must be so, then do this: take some of the choice fruits of the land in your bags, and carry them down as a present to the man--a little balm and a little honey, gum, resin, pistachio nuts, and almonds.
01â 43:12 Take double the money with you. Carry back with you the money that was returned in the top of your sacks; perhaps it was an oversight.
01â 43:13 Take your brother also, and be on your way again to the man;
01â 43:14 may God Almighty grant you mercy before the man, so that he may send back your other brother and Benjamin. As for me, if I am bereaved of my children, I am bereaved."
01â 43:15 So the men took the present, and they took double the money with them, as well as Benjamin. Then they went on their way down to Egypt, and stood before Joseph.
01â 43:16 When Joseph saw Benjamin with them, he said to the steward of his house, "Bring the men into the house, and slaughter an animal and make ready, for the men are to dine with me at noon."
01â 43:17 The man did as Joseph said, and brought the men to Joseph's house.
01â 43:18 Now the men were afraid because they were brought to Joseph's house, and they said, "It is because of the money, replaced in our sacks the first time, that we have been brought in, so that he may have an opportunity to fall upon us, to make slaves of us and take our donkeys."
01â 43:19 So they went up to the steward of Joseph's house and spoke with him at the entrance to the house.
01â 43:20 They said, "Oh, my lord, we came down the first time to buy food;
01â 43:21 and when we came to the lodging place we opened our sacks, and there was each one's money in the top of his sack, our money in full weight. So we have brought it back with us.
01â 43:22 Moreover we have brought down with us additional money to buy food. We do not know who put our money in our sacks."
01â 43:23 He replied, "Rest assured, do not be afraid; your God and the God of your father must have put treasure in your sacks for you; I received your money." Then he brought Simeon out to them.
01â 43:24 When the steward had brought the men into Joseph's house, and given them water, and they had washed their feet, and when he had given their donkeys fodder,
01â 43:25 they made the present ready for Joseph's coming at noon, for they had heard that they would dine there.
01â 43:26 When Joseph came home, they brought him the present that they had carried into the house, and bowed to the ground before him.
01â 43:27 He inquired about their welfare, and said, "Is your father well, the old man of whom you spoke? Is he still alive?"
01â 43:28 They said, "Your servant our father is well; he is still alive." And they bowed their heads and did obeisance.
01â 43:29 Then he looked up and saw his brother Benjamin, his mother's son, and said, "Is this your youngest brother, of whom you spoke to me? God be gracious to you, my son!"
01â 43:30 With that, Joseph hurried out, because he was overcome with affection for his brother, and he was about to weep. So he went into a private room and wept there.
01â 43:31 Then he washed his face and came out; and controlling himself he said, "Serve the meal."
01â 43:32 They served him by himself, and them by themselves, and the Egyptians who ate with him by themselves, because the Egyptians could not eat with the Hebrews, for that is an abomination to the Egyptians.
01â 43:33 When they were seated before him, the firstborn according to his birthright and the youngest according to his youth, the men looked at one another in amazement.
01â 43:34 Portions were taken to them from Joseph's table, but Benjamin's portion was five times as much as any of theirs. So they drank and were merry with him.
01â 44:1 Then he commanded the steward of his house, "Fill the men's sacks with food, as much as they can carry, and put each man's money in the top of his sack.
01â 44:2 Put my cup, the silver cup, in the top of the sack of the youngest, with his money for the grain." And he did as Joseph told him.
01â 44:3 As soon as the morning was light, the men were sent away with their donkeys.
01â 44:4 When they had gone only a short distance from the city, Joseph said to his steward, "Go, follow after the men; and when you overtake them, say to them, 'Why have you returned evil for good? Why have you stolen my silver cup?
01â 44:5 Is it not from this that my lord drinks? Does he not indeed use it for divination? You have done wrong in doing this.'"
01â 44:6 When he overtook them, he repeated these words to them.
01â 44:7 They said to him, "Why does my lord speak such words as these? Far be it from your servants that they should do such a thing!
01â 44:8 Look, the money that we found at the top of our sacks, we brought back to you from the land of Canaan; why then would we steal silver or gold from your lord's house?
01â 44:9 Should it be found with any one of your servants, let him die; moreover the rest of us will become my lord's slaves."
01â 44:10 He said, "Even so; in accordance with your words, let it be: he with whom it is found shall become my slave, but the rest of you shall go free."
01â 44:11 Then each one quickly lowered his sack to the ground, and each opened his sack.
01â 44:12 He searched, beginning with the eldest and ending with the youngest; and the cup was found in Benjamin's sack.
01â 44:13 At this they tore their clothes. Then each one loaded his donkey, and they returned to the city.
01â 44:14 Judah and his brothers came to Joseph's house while he was still there; and they fell to the ground before him.
01â 44:15 Joseph said to them, "What deed is this that you have done? Do you not know that one such as I can practice divination?"
01â 44:16 And Judah said, "What can we say to my lord? What can we speak? How can we clear ourselves? God has found out the guilt of your servants; here we are then, my lord's slaves, both we and also the one in whose possession the cup has been found."
01â 44:17 But he said, "Far be it from me that I should do so! Only the one in whose possession the cup was found shall be my slave; but as for you, go up in peace to your father."
01â 44:18 Then Judah stepped up to him and said, "O my lord, let your servant please speak a word in my lord's ears, and do not be angry with your servant; for you are like Pharaoh himself.
01â 44:19 My lord asked his servants, saying, 'Have you a father or a brother?'
01â 44:20 And we said to my lord, 'We have a father, an old man, and a young brother, the child of his old age. His brother is dead; he alone is left of his mother's children, and his father loves him.'
01â 44:21 Then you said to your servants, 'Bring him down to me, so that I may set my eyes on him.'
01â 44:22 We said to my lord, 'The boy cannot leave his father, for if he should leave his father, his father would die.'
01â 44:23 Then you said to your servants, 'Unless your youngest brother comes down with you, you shall see my face no more.'
01â 44:24 When we went back to your servant my father we told him the words of my lord.
01â 44:25 And when our father said, 'Go again, buy us a little food,'
01â 44:26 we said, 'We cannot go down. Only if our youngest brother goes with us, will we go down; for we cannot see the man's face unless our youngest brother is with us.'
01â 44:27 Then your servant my father said to us, 'You know that my wife bore me two sons;
01â 44:28 one left me, and I said, Surely he has been torn to pieces; and I have never seen him since.
01â 44:29 If you take this one also from me, and harm comes to him, you will bring down my gray hairs in sorrow to Sheol.'
01â 44:30 Now therefore, when I come to your servant my father and the boy is not with us, then, as his life is bound up in the boy's life,
01â 44:31 when he sees that the boy is not with us, he will die; and your servants will bring down the gray hairs of your servant our father with sorrow to Sheol.
01â 44:32 For your servant became surety for the boy to my father, saying, 'If I do not bring him back to you, then I will bear the blame in the sight of my father all my life.'
01â 44:33 Now therefore, please let your servant remain as a slave to my lord in place of the boy; and let the boy go back with his brothers.
01â 44:34 For how can I go back to my father if the boy is not with me? I fear to see the suffering that would come upon my father."
01â 45:1 Then Joseph could no longer control himself before all those who stood by him, and he cried out, "Send everyone away from me." So no one stayed with him when Joseph made himself known to his brothers.
01â 45:2 And he wept so loudly that the Egyptians heard it, and the household of Pharaoh heard it.
01â 45:3 Joseph said to his brothers, "I am Joseph. Is my father still alive?" But his brothers could not answer him, so dismayed were they at his presence.
01â 45:4 Then Joseph said to his brothers, "Come closer to me." And they came closer. He said, "I am your brother, Joseph, whom you sold into Egypt.
01â 45:5 And now do not be distressed, or angry with yourselves, because you sold me here; for God sent me before you to preserve life.
01â 45:6 For the famine has been in the land these two years; and there are five more years in which there will be neither plowing nor harvest.
01â 45:7 God sent me before you to preserve for you a remnant on earth, and to keep alive for you many survivors.
01â 45:8 So it was not you who sent me here, but God; he has made me a father to Pharaoh, and lord of all his house and ruler over all the land of Egypt.
01â 45:9 Hurry and go up to my father and say to him, 'Thus says your son Joseph, God has made me lord of all Egypt; come down to me, do not delay.
01â 45:10 You shall settle in the land of Goshen, and you shall be near me, you and your children and your children's children, as well as your flocks, your herds, and all that you have.
01â 45:11 I will provide for you there--since there are five more years of famine to come--so that you and your household, and all that you have, will not come to poverty.'
01â 45:12 And now your eyes and the eyes of my brother Benjamin see that it is my own mouth that speaks to you.
01â 45:13 You must tell my father how greatly I am honored in Egypt, and all that you have seen. Hurry and bring my father down here."
01â 45:14 Then he fell upon his brother Benjamin's neck and wept, while Benjamin wept upon his neck.
01â 45:15 And he kissed all his brothers and wept upon them; and after that his brothers talked with him.
01â 45:16 When the report was heard in Pharaoh's house, "Joseph's brothers have come," Pharaoh and his servants were pleased.
01â 45:17 Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Say to your brothers, 'Do this: load your animals and go back to the land of Canaan.
01â 45:18 Take your father and your households and come to me, so that I may give you the best of the land of Egypt, and you may enjoy the fat of the land.'
01â 45:19 You are further charged to say, 'Do this: take wagons from the land of Egypt for your little ones and for your wives, and bring your father, and come.
01â 45:20 Give no thought to your possessions, for the best of all the land of Egypt is yours.'"
01â 45:21 The sons of Israel did so. Joseph gave them wagons according to the instruction of Pharaoh, and he gave them provisions for the journey.
01â 45:22 To each one of them he gave a set of garments; but to Benjamin he gave three hundred pieces of silver and five sets of garments.
01â 45:23 To his father he sent the following: ten donkeys loaded with the good things of Egypt, and ten female donkeys loaded with grain, bread, and provision for his father on the journey.
01â 45:24 Then he sent his brothers on their way, and as they were leaving he said to them, "Do not quarrel along the way."
01â 45:25 So they went up out of Egypt and came to their father Jacob in the land of Canaan.
01â 45:26 And they told him, "Joseph is still alive! He is even ruler over all the land of Egypt." He was stunned; he could not believe them.
01â 45:27 But when they told him all the words of Joseph that he had said to them, and when he saw the wagons that Joseph had sent to carry him, the spirit of their father Jacob revived.
01â 45:28 Israel said, "Enough! My son Joseph is still alive. I must go and see him before I die."
01â 46:1 When Israel set out on his journey with all that he had and came to Beer-sheba, he offered sacrifices to the God of his father Isaac.
01â 46:2 God spoke to Israel in visions of the night, and said, "Jacob, Jacob." And he said, "Here I am."
01â 46:3 Then he said, "I am God, the God of your father; do not be afraid to go down to Egypt, for I will make of you a great nation there.
01â 46:4 I myself will go down with you to Egypt, and I will also bring you up again; and Joseph's own hand shall close your eyes."
01â 46:5 Then Jacob set out from Beer-sheba; and the sons of Israel carried their father Jacob, their little ones, and their wives, in the wagons that Pharaoh had sent to carry him.
01â 46:6 They also took their livestock and the goods that they had acquired in the land of Canaan, and they came into Egypt, Jacob and all his offspring with him,
01â 46:7 his sons, and his sons' sons with him, his daughters, and his sons' daughters; all his offspring he brought with him into Egypt.
01â 46:8 Now these are the names of the Israelites, Jacob and his offspring, who came to Egypt. Reuben, Jacob's firstborn,
01â 46:9 and the children of Reuben: Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.
01â 46:10 The children of Simeon: Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jachin, Zohar, and Shaul, the son of a Canaanite woman.
01â 46:11 The children of Levi: Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.
01â 46:12 The children of Judah: Er, Onan, Shelah, Perez, and Zerah (but Er and Onan died in the land of Canaan); and the children of Perez were Hezron and Hamul.
01â 46:13 The children of Issachar: Tola, Puvah, Jashub, and Shimron.
01â 46:14 The children of Zebulun: Sered, Elon, and Jahleel
01â 46:15 (these are the sons of Leah, whom she bore to Jacob in Paddan-aram, together with his daughter Dinah; in all his sons and his daughters numbered thirty-three).
01â 46:16 The children of Gad: Ziphion, Haggi, Shuni, Ezbon, Eri, Arodi, and Areli.
01â 46:17 The children of Asher: Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, Beriah, and their sister Serah. The children of Beriah: Heber and Malchiel
01â 46:18 (these are the children of Zilpah, whom Laban gave to his daughter Leah; and these she bore to Jacob--sixteen persons).
01â 46:19 The children of Jacob's wife Rachel: Joseph and Benjamin.
01â 46:20 To Joseph in the land of Egypt were born Manasseh and Ephraim, whom Asenath daughter of Potiphera, priest of On, bore to him.
01â 46:21 The children of Benjamin: Bela, Becher, Ashbel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi, Rosh, Muppim, Huppim, and Ard
01â 46:22 (these are the children of Rachel, who were born to Jacob--fourteen persons in all).
01â 46:23 The children of Dan: Hashum.
01â 46:24 The children of Naphtali: Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, and Shillem
01â 46:25 (these are the children of Bilhah, whom Laban gave to his daughter Rachel, and these she bore to Jacob--seven persons in all).
01â 46:26 All the persons belonging to Jacob who came into Egypt, who were his own offspring, not including the wives of his sons, were sixty-six persons in all.
01â 46:27 The children of Joseph, who were born to him in Egypt, were two; all the persons of the house of Jacob who came into Egypt were seventy.
01â 46:28 Israel sent Judah ahead to Joseph to lead the way before him into Goshen. When they came to the land of Goshen,
01â 46:29 Joseph made ready his chariot and went up to meet his father Israel in Goshen. He presented himself to him, fell on his neck, and wept on his neck a good while.
01â 46:30 Israel said to Joseph, "I can die now, having seen for myself that you are still alive."
01â 46:31 Joseph said to his brothers and to his father's household, "I will go up and tell Pharaoh, and will say to him, 'My brothers and my father's household, who were in the land of Canaan, have come to me.
01â 46:32 The men are shepherds, for they have been keepers of livestock; and they have brought their flocks, and their herds, and all that they have.'
01â 46:33 When Pharaoh calls you, and says, 'What is your occupation?'
01â 46:34 you shall say, 'Your servants have been keepers of livestock from our youth even until now, both we and our ancestors'--in order that you may settle in the land of Goshen, because all shepherds are abhorrent to the Egyptians."
01â 47:1 So Joseph went and told Pharaoh, "My father and my brothers, with their flocks and herds and all that they possess, have come from the land of Canaan; they are now in the land of Goshen."
01â 47:2 From among his brothers he took five men and presented them to Pharaoh.
01â 47:3 Pharaoh said to his brothers, "What is your occupation?" And they said to Pharaoh, "Your servants are shepherds, as our ancestors were."
01â 47:4 They said to Pharaoh, "We have come to reside as aliens in the land; for there is no pasture for your servants' flocks because the famine is severe in the land of Canaan. Now, we ask you, let your servants settle in the land of Goshen."
01â 47:5 Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, "Your father and your brothers have come to you.
01â 47:6 The land of Egypt is before you; settle your father and your brothers in the best part of the land; let them live in the land of Goshen; and if you know that there are capable men among them, put them in charge of my livestock."
01â 47:7 Then Joseph brought in his father Jacob, and presented him before Pharaoh, and Jacob blessed Pharaoh.
01â 47:8 Pharaoh said to Jacob, "How many are the years of your life?"
01â 47:9 Jacob said to Pharaoh, "The years of my earthly sojourn are one hundred thirty; few and hard have been the years of my life. They do not compare with the years of the life of my ancestors during their long sojourn."
01â 47:10 Then Jacob blessed Pharaoh, and went out from the presence of Pharaoh.
01â 47:11 Joseph settled his father and his brothers, and granted them a holding in the land of Egypt, in the best part of the land, in the land of Rameses, as Pharaoh had instructed.
01â 47:12 And Joseph provided his father, his brothers, and all his father's household with food, according to the number of their dependents.
01â 47:13 Now there was no food in all the land, for the famine was very severe. The land of Egypt and the land of Canaan languished because of the famine.
01â 47:14 Joseph collected all the money to be found in the land of Egypt and in the land of Canaan, in exchange for the grain that they bought; and Joseph brought the money into Pharaoh's house.
01â 47:15 When the money from the land of Egypt and from the land of Canaan was spent, all the Egyptians came to Joseph, and said, "Give us food! Why should we die before your eyes? For our money is gone."
01â 47:16 And Joseph answered, "Give me your livestock, and I will give you food in exchange for your livestock, if your money is gone."
01â 47:17 So they brought their livestock to Joseph; and Joseph gave them food in exchange for the horses, the flocks, the herds, and the donkeys. That year he supplied them with food in exchange for all their livestock.
01â 47:18 When that year was ended, they came to him the following year, and said to him, "We can not hide from my lord that our money is all spent; and the herds of cattle are my lord's. There is nothing left in the sight of my lord but our bodies and our lands.
01â 47:19 Shall we die before your eyes, both we and our land? Buy us and our land in exchange for food. We with our land will become slaves to Pharaoh; just give us seed, so that we may live and not die, and that the land may not become desolate."
01â 47:20 So Joseph bought all the land of Egypt for Pharaoh. All the Egyptians sold their fields, because the famine was severe upon them; and the land became Pharaoh's.
01â 47:21 As for the people, he made slaves of them from one end of Egypt to the other.
01â 47:22 Only the land of the priests he did not buy; for the priests had a fixed allowance from Pharaoh, and lived on the allowance that Pharaoh gave them; therefore they did not sell their land.
01â 47:23 Then Joseph said to the people, "Now that I have this day bought you and your land for Pharaoh, here is seed for you; sow the land.
01â 47:24 And at the harvests you shall give one-fifth to Pharaoh, and four-fifths shall be your own, as seed for the field and as food for yourselves and your households, and as food for your little ones."
01â 47:25 They said, "You have saved our lives; may it please my lord, we will be slaves to Pharaoh."
01â 47:26 So Joseph made it a statute concerning the land of Egypt, and it stands to this day, that Pharaoh should have the fifth. The land of the priests alone did not become Pharaoh's.
01â 47:27 Thus Israel settled in the land of Egypt, in the region of Goshen; and they gained possessions in it, and were fruitful and multiplied exceedingly.
01â 47:28 Jacob lived in the land of Egypt seventeen years; so the days of Jacob, the years of his life, were one hundred forty-seven years.
01â 47:29 When the time of Israel's death drew near, he called his son Joseph and said to him, "If I have found favor with you, put your hand under my thigh and promise to deal loyally and truly with me. Do not bury me in Egypt.
01â 47:30 When I lie down with my ancestors, carry me out of Egypt and bury me in their burial place." He answered, "I will do as you have said."
01â 47:31 And he said, "Swear to me"; and he swore to him. Then Israel bowed himself on the head of his bed.
01â 48:1 After this Joseph was told, "Your father is ill." So he took with him his two sons, Manasseh and Ephraim.
01â 48:2 When Jacob was told, "Your son Joseph has come to you," he summoned his strength and sat up in bed.
01â 48:3 And Jacob said to Joseph, "God Almighty appeared to me at Luz in the land of Canaan, and he blessed me,
01â 48:4 and said to me, 'I am going to make you fruitful and increase your numbers; I will make of you a company of peoples, and will give this land to your offspring after you for a perpetual holding.'
01â 48:5 Therefore your two sons, who were born to you in the land of Egypt before I came to you in Egypt, are now mine; Ephraim and Manasseh shall be mine, just as Reuben and Simeon are.
01â 48:6 As for the offspring born to you after them, they shall be yours. They shall be recorded under the names of their brothers with regard to their inheritance.
01â 48:7 For when I came from Paddan, Rachel, alas, died in the land of Canaan on the way, while there was still some distance to go to Ephrath; and I buried her there on the way to Ephrath" (that is, Bethlehem).
01â 48:8 When Israel saw Joseph's sons, he said, "Who are these?"
01â 48:9 Joseph said to his father, "They are my sons, whom God has given me here." And he said, "Bring them to me, please, that I may bless them."
01â 48:10 Now the eyes of Israel were dim with age, and he could not see well. So Joseph brought them near him; and he kissed them and embraced them.
01â 48:11 Israel said to Joseph, "I did not expect to see your face; and here God has let me see your children also."
01â 48:12 Then Joseph removed them from his father's knees, and he bowed himself with his face to the earth.
01â 48:13 Joseph took them both, Ephraim in his right hand toward Israel's left, and Manasseh in his left hand toward Israel's right, and brought them near him.
01â 48:14 But Israel stretched out his right hand and laid it on the head of Ephraim, who was the younger, and his left hand on the head of Manasseh, crossing his hands, for Manasseh was the firstborn.
01â 48:15 He blessed Joseph, and said, "The God before whom my ancestors Abraham and Isaac walked, the God who has been my shepherd all my life to this day,
01â 48:16 the angel who has redeemed me from all harm, bless the boys; and in them let my name be perpetuated, and the name of my ancestors Abraham and Isaac; and let them grow into a multitude on the earth."
01â 48:17 When Joseph saw that his father laid his right hand on the head of Ephraim, it displeased him; so he took his father's hand, to remove it from Ephraim's head to Manasseh's head.
01â 48:18 Joseph said to his father, "Not so, my father! Since this one is the firstborn, put your right hand on his head."
01â 48:19 But his father refused, and said, "I know, my son, I know; he also shall become a people, and he also shall be great. Nevertheless his younger brother shall be greater than he, and his offspring shall become a multitude of nations."
01â 48:20 So he blessed them that day, saying, "By you Israel will invoke blessings, saying, 'God make you like Ephraim and like Manasseh.'" So he put Ephraim ahead of Manasseh.
01â 48:21 Then Israel said to Joseph, "I am about to die, but God will be with you and will bring you again to the land of your ancestors.
01â 48:22 I now give to you one portion more than to your brothers, the portion that I took from the hand of the Amorites with my sword and with my bow."
01â 49:1 Then Jacob called his sons, and said: "Gather around, that I may tell you what will happen to you in days to come.
01â 49:2 Assemble and hear, O sons of Jacob; listen to Israel your father.
01â 49:3 Reuben, you are my firstborn, my might and the first fruits of my vigor, excelling in rank and excelling in power.
01â 49:4 Unstable as water, you shall no longer excel because you went up onto your father's bed; then you defiled it--you went up onto my couch!
01â 49:5 Simeon and Levi are brothers; weapons of violence are their swords.
01â 49:6 May I never come into their council; may I not be joined to their company--for in their anger they killed men, and at their whim they hamstrung oxen.
01â 49:7 Cursed be their anger, for it is fierce, and their wrath, for it is cruel! I will divide them in Jacob, and scatter them in Israel.
01â 49:8 Judah, your brothers shall praise you; your hand shall be on the neck of your enemies; your father's sons shall bow down before you.
01â 49:9 Judah is a lion's whelp; from the prey, my son, you have gone up. He crouches down, he stretches out like a lion, like a lioness--who dares rouse him up?
01â 49:10 The scepter shall not depart from Judah, nor the ruler's staff from between his feet, until tribute comes to him; and the obedience of the peoples is his.
01â 49:11 Binding his foal to the vine and his donkey's colt to the choice vine, he washes his garments in wine and his robe in the blood of grapes;
01â 49:12 his eyes are darker than wine, and his teeth whiter than milk.
01â 49:13 Zebulun shall settle at the shore of the sea; he shall be a haven for ships, and his border shall be at Sidon.
01â 49:14 Issachar is a strong donkey, lying down between the sheepfolds;
01â 49:15 he saw that a resting place was good, and that the land was pleasant; so he bowed his shoulder to the burden, and became a slave at forced labor.
01â 49:16 Dan shall judge his people as one of the tribes of Israel.
01â 49:17 Dan shall be a snake by the roadside, a viper along the path, that bites the horse's heels so that its rider falls backward.
01â 49:18 I wait for your salvation, O LORD.
01â 49:19 Gad shall be raided by raiders, but he shall raid at their heels.
01â 49:20 Asher's food shall be rich, and he shall provide royal delicacies.
01â 49:21 Naphtali is a doe let loose that bears lovely fawns.
01â 49:22 Joseph is a fruitful bough, a fruitful bough by a spring; his branches run over the wall.
01â 49:23 The archers fiercely attacked him; they shot at him and pressed him hard.
01â 49:24 Yet his bow remained taut, and his arms were made agile by the hands of the Mighty One of Jacob, by the name of the Shepherd, the Rock of Israel,
01â 49:25 by the God of your father, who will help you, by the Almighty who will bless you with blessings of heaven above, blessings of the deep that lies beneath, blessings of the breasts and of the womb.
01â 49:26 The blessings of your father are stronger than the blessings of the eternal mountains, the bounties of the everlasting hills; may they be on the head of Joseph, on the brow of him who was set apart from his brothers.
01â 49:27 Benjamin is a ravenous wolf, in the morning devouring the prey, and at evening dividing the spoil."
01â 49:28 All these are the twelve tribes of Israel, and this is what their father said to them when he blessed them, blessing each one of them with a suitable blessing.
01â 49:29 Then he charged them, saying to them, "I am about to be gathered to my people. Bury me with my ancestors--in the cave in the field of Ephron the Hittite,
01â 49:30 in the cave in the field at Machpelah, near Mamre, in the land of Canaan, in the field that Abraham bought from Ephron the Hittite as a burial site.
01â 49:31 There Abraham and his wife Sarah were buried; there Isaac and his wife Rebekah were buried; and there I buried Leah--
01â 49:32 the field and the cave that is in it were purchased from the Hittites."
01â 49:33 When Jacob ended his charge to his sons, he drew up his feet into the bed, breathed his last, and was gathered to his people.
01â 50:1 Then Joseph threw himself on his father's face and wept over him and kissed him.
01â 50:2 Joseph commanded the physicians in his service to embalm his father. So the physicians embalmed Israel;
01â 50:3 they spent forty days in doing this, for that is the time required for embalming. And the Egyptians wept for him seventy days.
01â 50:4 When the days of weeping for him were past, Joseph addressed the household of Pharaoh, "If now I have found favor with you, please speak to Pharaoh as follows:
01â 50:5 My father made me swear an oath; he said, 'I am about to die. In the tomb that I hewed out for myself in the land of Canaan, there you shall bury me.' Now therefore let me go up, so that I may bury my father; then I will return."
01â 50:6 Pharaoh answered, "Go up, and bury your father, as he made you swear to do."
01â 50:7 So Joseph went up to bury his father. With him went up all the servants of Pharaoh, the elders of his household, and all the elders of the land of Egypt,
01â 50:8 as well as all the household of Joseph, his brothers, and his father's household. Only their children, their flocks, and their herds were left in the land of Goshen.
01â 50:9 Both chariots and charioteers went up with him. It was a very great company.
01â 50:10 When they came to the threshing floor of Atad, which is beyond the Jordan, they held there a very great and sorrowful lamentation; and he observed a time of mourning for his father seven days.
01â 50:11 When the Canaanite inhabitants of the land saw the mourning on the threshing floor of Atad, they said, "This is a grievous mourning on the part of the Egyptians." Therefore the place was named Abel-mizraim; it is beyond the Jordan.
01â 50:12 Thus his sons did for him as he had instructed them.
01â 50:13 They carried him to the land of Canaan and buried him in the cave of the field at Machpelah, the field near Mamre, which Abraham bought as a burial site from Ephron the Hittite.
01â 50:14 After he had buried his father, Joseph returned to Egypt with his brothers and all who had gone up with him to bury his father.
01â 50:15 Realizing that their father was dead, Joseph's brothers said, "What if Joseph still bears a grudge against us and pays us back in full for all the wrong that we did to him?"
01â 50:16 So they approached Joseph, saying, "Your father gave this instruction before he died,
01â 50:17 'Say to Joseph: I beg you, forgive the crime of your brothers and the wrong they did in harming you.' Now therefore please forgive the crime of the servants of the God of your father." Joseph wept when they spoke to him.
01â 50:18 Then his brothers also wept, fell down before him, and said, "We are here as your slaves."
01â 50:19 But Joseph said to them, "Do not be afraid! Am I in the place of God?
01â 50:20 Even though you intended to do harm to me, God intended it for good, in order to preserve a numerous people, as he is doing today.
01â 50:21 So have no fear; I myself will provide for you and your little ones." In this way he reassured them, speaking kindly to them.
01â 50:22 So Joseph remained in Egypt, he and his father's household; and Joseph lived one hundred ten years.
01â 50:23 Joseph saw Ephraim's children of the third generation; the children of Machir son of Manasseh were also born on Joseph's knees.
01â 50:24 Then Joseph said to his brothers, "I am about to die; but God will surely come to you, and bring you up out of this land to the land that he swore to Abraham, to Isaac, and to Jacob."
01â 50:25 So Joseph made the Israelites swear, saying, "When God comes to you, you shall carry up my bones from here."
01â 50:26 And Joseph died, being one hundred ten years old; he was embalmed and placed in a coffin in Egypt.
