02 12:1 The LORD said to Moses and Aaron in the land of Egypt:
02 12:2 This month shall mark for you the beginning of months; it shall be the first month of the year for you.
02 12:3 Tell the whole congregation of Israel that on the tenth of this month they are to take a lamb for each family, a lamb for each household.
02 12:4 If a household is too small for a whole lamb, it shall join its closest neighbor in obtaining one; the lamb shall be divided in proportion to the number of people who eat of it.
02 12:5 Your lamb shall be without blemish, a year-old male; you may take it from the sheep or from the goats.
02 12:6 You shall keep it until the fourteenth day of this month; then the whole assembled congregation of Israel shall slaughter it at twilight.
02 12:7 They shall take some of the blood and put it on the two doorposts and the lintel of the houses in which they eat it.
02 12:8 They shall eat the lamb that same night; they shall eat it roasted over the fire with unleavened bread and bitter herbs.
02 12:9 Do not eat any of it raw or boiled in water, but roasted over the fire, with its head, legs, and inner organs.
02 12:10 You shall let none of it remain until the morning; anything that remains until the morning you shall burn.
02 12:11 This is how you shall eat it: your loins girded, your sandals on your feet, and your staff in your hand; and you shall eat it hurriedly. It is the passover of the LORD.
02 12:12 For I will pass through the land of Egypt that night, and I will strike down every firstborn in the land of Egypt, both human beings and animals; on all the gods of Egypt I will execute judgments: I am the LORD.
02 12:13 The blood shall be a sign for you on the houses where you live: when I see the blood, I will pass over you, and no plague shall destroy you when I strike the land of Egypt.
02 12:14 This day shall be a day of remembrance for you. You shall celebrate it as a festival to the LORD; throughout your generations you shall observe it as a perpetual ordinance.
02 12:15 Seven days you shall eat unleavened bread; on the first day you shall remove leaven from your houses, for whoever eats leavened bread from the first day until the seventh day shall be cut off from Israel.
02 12:16 On the first day you shall hold a solemn assembly, and on the seventh day a solemn assembly; no work shall be done on those days; only what everyone must eat, that alone may be prepared by you.
02 12:17 You shall observe the festival of unleavened bread, for on this very day I brought your companies out of the land of Egypt: you shall observe this day throughout your generations as a perpetual ordinance.
02 12:18 In the first month, from the evening of the fourteenth day until the evening of the twenty-first day, you shall eat unleavened bread.
02 12:19 For seven days no leaven shall be found in your houses; for whoever eats what is leavened shall be cut off from the congregation of Israel, whether an alien or a native of the land.
02 12:20 You shall eat nothing leavened; in all your settlements you shall eat unleavened bread.
02 12:21 Then Moses called all the elders of Israel and said to them, "Go, select lambs for your families, and slaughter the passover lamb.
02 12:22 Take a bunch of hyssop, dip it in the blood that is in the basin, and touch the lintel and the two doorposts with the blood in the basin. None of you shall go outside the door of your house until morning.
02 12:23 For the LORD will pass through to strike down the Egyptians; when he sees the blood on the lintel and on the two doorposts, the LORD will pass over that door and will not allow the destroyer to enter your houses to strike you down.
02 12:24 You shall observe this rite as a perpetual ordinance for you and your children.
02 12:25 When you come to the land that the LORD will give you, as he has promised, you shall keep this observance.
02 12:26 And when your children ask you, 'What do you mean by this observance?'
02 12:27 you shall say, 'It is the passover sacrifice to the LORD, for he passed over the houses of the Israelites in Egypt, when he struck down the Egyptians but spared our houses.'" And the people bowed down and worshiped.
02 12:28 The Israelites went and did just as the LORD had commanded Moses and Aaron.
02 12:29 At midnight the LORD struck down all the firstborn in the land of Egypt, from the firstborn of Pharaoh who sat on his throne to the firstborn of the prisoner who was in the dungeon, and all the firstborn of the livestock.
02 12:30 Pharaoh arose in the night, he and all his officials and all the Egyptians; and there was a loud cry in Egypt, for there was not a house without someone dead.
02 12:31 Then he summoned Moses and Aaron in the night, and said, "Rise up, go away from my people, both you and the Israelites! Go, worship the LORD, as you said.
02 12:32 Take your flocks and your herds, as you said, and be gone. And bring a blessing on me too!"
02 12:33 The Egyptians urged the people to hasten their departure from the land, for they said, "We shall all be dead."
02 12:34 So the people took their dough before it was leavened, with their kneading bowls wrapped up in their cloaks on their shoulders.
02 12:35 The Israelites had done as Moses told them; they had asked the Egyptians for jewelry of silver and gold, and for clothing,
02 12:36 and the LORD had given the people favor in the sight of the Egyptians, so that they let them have what they asked. And so they plundered the Egyptians.
02 12:37 The Israelites journeyed from Rameses to Succoth, about six hundred thousand men on foot, besides children.
02 12:38 A mixed crowd also went up with them, and livestock in great numbers, both flocks and herds.
02 12:39 They baked unleavened cakes of the dough that they had brought out of Egypt; it was not leavened, because they were driven out of Egypt and could not wait, nor had they prepared any provisions for themselves.
02 12:40 The time that the Israelites had lived in Egypt was four hundred thirty years.
02 12:41 At the end of four hundred thirty years, on that very day, all the companies of the LORD went out from the land of Egypt.
02 12:42 That was for the LORD a night of vigil, to bring them out of the land of Egypt. That same night is a vigil to be kept for the LORD by all the Israelites throughout their generations.
02 12:43 The LORD said to Moses and Aaron: This is the ordinance for the passover: no foreigner shall eat of it,
02 12:44 but any slave who has been purchased may eat of it after he has been circumcised;
02 12:45 no bound or hired servant may eat of it.
02 12:46 It shall be eaten in one house; you shall not take any of the animal outside the house, and you shall not break any of its bones.
02 12:47 The whole congregation of Israel shall celebrate it.
02 12:48 If an alien who resides with you wants to celebrate the passover to the LORD, all his males shall be circumcised; then he may draw near to celebrate it; he shall be regarded as a native of the land. But no uncircumcised person shall eat of it;
02 12:49 there shall be one law for the native and for the alien who resides among you.
02 12:50 All the Israelites did just as the LORD had commanded Moses and Aaron.
02 12:51 That very day the LORD brought the Israelites out of the land of Egypt, company by company.
02 13:1 The LORD said to Moses:
02 13:2 Consecrate to me all the firstborn; whatever is the first to open the womb among the Israelites, of human beings and animals, is mine.
02 13:3 Moses said to the people, "Remember this day on which you came out of Egypt, out of the house of slavery, because the LORD brought you out from there by strength of hand; no leavened bread shall be eaten.
02 13:4 Today, in the month of Abib, you are going out.
02 13:5 When the LORD brings you into the land of the Canaanites, the Hittites, the Amorites, the Hivites, and the Jebusites, which he swore to your ancestors to give you, a land flowing with milk and honey, you shall keep this observance in this month.
02 13:6 Seven days you shall eat unleavened bread, and on the seventh day there shall be a festival to the LORD.
02 13:7 Unleavened bread shall be eaten for seven days; no leavened bread shall be seen in your possession, and no leaven shall be seen among you in all your territory.
02 13:8 You shall tell your child on that day, 'It is because of what the LORD did for me when I came out of Egypt.'
02 13:9 It shall serve for you as a sign on your hand and as a reminder on your forehead, so that the teaching of the LORD may be on your lips; for with a strong hand the LORD brought you out of Egypt.
02 13:10 You shall keep this ordinance at its proper time from year to year.
02 13:11 "When the LORD has brought you into the land of the Canaanites, as he swore to you and your ancestors, and has given it to you,
02 13:12 you shall set apart to the LORD all that first opens the womb. All the firstborn of your livestock that are males shall be the LORD's.
02 13:13 But every firstborn donkey you shall redeem with a sheep; if you do not redeem it, you must break its neck. Every firstborn male among your children you shall redeem.
02 13:14 When in the future your child asks you, 'What does this mean?' you shall answer, 'By strength of hand the LORD brought us out of Egypt, from the house of slavery.
02 13:15 When Pharaoh stubbornly refused to let us go, the LORD killed all the firstborn in the land of Egypt, from human firstborn to the firstborn of animals. Therefore I sacrifice to the LORD every male that first opens the womb, but every firstborn of my sons I redeem.'
02 13:16 It shall serve as a sign on your hand and as an emblem on your forehead that by strength of hand the LORD brought us out of Egypt."
02 13:17 When Pharaoh let the people go, God did not lead them by way of the land of the Philistines, although that was nearer; for God thought, "If the people face war, they may change their minds and return to Egypt."
02 13:18 So God led the people by the roundabout way of the wilderness toward the Red Sea. The Israelites went up out of the land of Egypt prepared for battle.
02 13:19 And Moses took with him the bones of Joseph who had required a solemn oath of the Israelites, saying, "God will surely take notice of you, and then you must carry my bones with you from here."
02 13:20 They set out from Succoth, and camped at Etham, on the edge of the wilderness.
02 13:21 The LORD went in front of them in a pillar of cloud by day, to lead them along the way, and in a pillar of fire by night, to give them light, so that they might travel by day and by night.
02 13:22 Neither the pillar of cloud by day nor the pillar of fire by night left its place in front of the people.
02 14:1 Then the LORD said to Moses:
02 14:2 Tell the Israelites to turn back and camp in front of Pi-hahiroth, between Migdol and the sea, in front of Baal-zephon; you shall camp opposite it, by the sea.
02 14:3 Pharaoh will say of the Israelites, 'They are wandering aimlessly in the land; the wilderness has closed in on them.'
02 14:4 I will harden Pharaoh's heart, and he will pursue them, so that I will gain glory for myself over Pharaoh and all his army; and the Egyptians shall know that I am the LORD. And they did so.
02 14:5 When the king of Egypt was told that the people had fled, the minds of Pharaoh and his officials were changed toward the people, and they said, "What have we done, letting Israel leave our service?"
02 14:6 So he had his chariot made ready, and took his army with him;
02 14:7 he took six hundred picked chariots and all the other chariots of Egypt with officers over all of them.
02 14:8 The LORD hardened the heart of Pharaoh king of Egypt and he pursued the Israelites, who were going out boldly.
02 14:9 The Egyptians pursued them, all Pharaoh's horses and chariots, his chariot drivers and his army; they overtook them camped by the sea, by Pi-hahiroth, in front of Baal-zephon.
02 14:10 As Pharaoh drew near, the Israelites looked back, and there were the Egyptians advancing on them. In great fear the Israelites cried out to the LORD.
